<!-- ===== SECTION 1: ANDROID ===== -->
<section class="section" id="android">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-num">01</div>
    <div class="section-title-wrap">
      <div class="section-tag">Native Platform Deep Dive</div>
      <h1 class="section-title">Android Native Engineering</h1>
      <p class="section-desc">Complete Android internals for React Native engineers moving to Senior/Lead/Staff. From Activity lifecycle to JNI, Gradle, Kotlin coroutines, and production debugging.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="tags">
    <span class="badge badge-android">Android</span>
    <span class="tag">Activity Lifecycle</span>
    <span class="tag">Gradle</span>
    <span class="tag">Kotlin</span>
    <span class="tag">JNI</span>
    <span class="tag">ART</span>
    <span class="tag">Binder IPC</span>
  </div>

  <h2>Android Architecture Fundamentals</h2>

  <h3>Activity Lifecycle — The Complete Picture</h3>
  <p>Most engineers know onCreate/onResume. Staff engineers know <em>why</em> they exist and how process death, configuration changes, and back-stack interact.</p>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
ACTIVITY LIFECYCLE (Full State Machine)

  App Launch
      │
      ▼
  onCreate()  ←──────────────────────────────┐
      │         (savedInstanceState)          │
      ▼                                       │
  onStart()                                   │ Activity
      │                                       │ Recreated
      ▼                                       │ (rotation,
  onResume()  ◄── VISIBLE & INTERACTIVE       │  locale change)
      │                                       │
      │ (another activity comes to foreground)│
      ▼                                       │
  onPause()  ─── save lightweight state       │
      │                                       │
      │ (activity fully hidden)               │
      ▼                                       │
  onStop()  ─── release heavy resources       │
      │                                       │
      ├─────────────────────────────────────→─┘
      │ (configuration change: destroys+recreates)
      │
      │ (user back, or OS kills process)
      ▼
  onDestroy()
      │
      ▼
  Process may be killed (low memory)
  savedInstanceState persists ✓
  ViewModel survives config change ✓
</pre>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-danger">
    <span class="callout-icon">⚠️</span>
    <div class="callout-content">
      <div class="callout-title">Process Death — The Silent Killer</div>
      Android can kill your process while it's in the background. When the user returns, the OS recreates the Activity from savedInstanceState. Any in-memory state (ViewModel data, global singletons) is gone. React Native apps frequently crash on restoration because JS state isn't persisted. Staff engineers ensure persistence through SharedPreferences, Room, or MMKV + proper ViewModel + SavedStateHandle.
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Key Lifecycle Callbacks for RN Engineers</h3>

  <pre data-lang="Kotlin"><code><span class="kw">class</span> <span class="type">MainActivity</span> : <span class="type">ReactActivity</span>() {

    <span class="cm">// Called ONCE. View not yet inflated.</span>
    <span class="kw">override fun</span> <span class="fn">onCreate</span>(savedInstanceState: <span class="type">Bundle</span>?) {
        <span class="cm">// RN: Don't call super.onCreate too early—causes "Already managing a dialog"</span>
        <span class="kw">super</span>.onCreate(savedInstanceState)
        <span class="cm">// Splash screen, initial state restoration</span>
    }

    <span class="cm">// Called every time activity becomes visible</span>
    <span class="kw">override fun</span> <span class="fn">onResume</span>() {
        <span class="kw">super</span>.onResume()
        <span class="cm">// RN: AppState 'active' fires here</span>
        <span class="cm">// Resume sensors, location, network listeners</span>
    }

    <span class="cm">// Configuration change (rotation, dark mode, locale)</span>
    <span class="kw">override fun</span> <span class="fn">onConfigurationChanged</span>(newConfig: <span class="type">Configuration</span>) {
        <span class="kw">super</span>.onConfigurationChanged(newConfig)
        <span class="cm">// RN new arch: Fabric handles this natively</span>
        <span class="cm">// Old arch: must emit config change event to JS</span>
    }

    <span class="cm">// Save lightweight, serializable state</span>
    <span class="kw">override fun</span> <span class="fn">onSaveInstanceState</span>(outState: <span class="type">Bundle</span>) {
        <span class="kw">super</span>.onSaveInstanceState(outState)
        outState.putString(<span class="str">"key"</span>, viewModel.currentRoute)
    }
}</code></pre>

  <h3>Fragment Lifecycle & Why It Matters for RN</h3>
  <p>React Native's <code>ReactRootView</code> is often embedded inside a Fragment in hybrid apps. Understanding Fragment lifecycle prevents common issues like duplicate RN instances and memory leaks.</p>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
FRAGMENT LIFECYCLE

  onAttach()      → Fragment attached to Activity
  onCreate()      → Fragment created (no view yet)
  onCreateView()  → Inflate layout → ReactRootView goes here
  onViewCreated() → View ready → start RN bundle
  onStart()
  onResume()
  ──── USER SEES FRAGMENT ────
  onPause()
  onStop()
  onDestroyView() → DETACH ReactRootView here (critical!)
  onDestroy()
  onDetach()

  Common RN Bug: Not calling reactRootView.unmountReactApplication()
  in onDestroyView() → memory leak + JS state corruption
</pre>
  </div>

  <h3>Android Services</h3>
  <div class="card-grid">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">Foreground Service</div>
      <div class="card-body">Runs with persistent notification. Required for audio playback, location tracking, file downloads. RN: react-native-track-player uses this. Android 14+ requires declaring foreground service type in manifest.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">Background Service</div>
      <div class="card-body">Deprecated for long work. Use WorkManager instead. Background services are killed aggressively on API 26+. Common mistake: using old IntentService for background sync in RN apps.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">Bound Service</div>
      <div class="card-body">Allows IPC via AIDL or Messenger. Used for in-app billing, DRM, Bluetooth. RN TurboModules don't use this—they use JSI. Staff engineers understand AIDL for complex native integrations.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Android Threading Model</h3>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
ANDROID THREADING MODEL

Main Thread (UI Thread)
├── Looper (infinite message queue)
├── MessageQueue (FIFO)
├── Handler (posts to MessageQueue)
├── Choreographer (vsync-driven frame callbacks)
└── ViewRootImpl (measure/layout/draw)

Background Threads
├── AsyncTask (deprecated API 30)
├── Thread/ExecutorService
├── Kotlin Coroutines (recommended)
└── WorkManager (deferred/periodic work)

React Native Threading (Old Arch)
├── Main Thread      → UI operations
├── JS Thread        → JavaScript execution
├── Shadow Thread    → Yoga layout
└── Native Modules   → separate thread pool

React Native Threading (New Arch)
├── Main Thread      → Fabric UI sync
├── JS Thread        → JS runtime (Hermes)
├── Render Thread    → Skia (if used)
└── Background Pools → TurboModule work
</pre>
  </div>

  <h3>Looper & Handler Internals</h3>
  <p>Every Android thread can have a <code>Looper</code> — an infinite loop that dequeues <code>Message</code>s and dispatches them to a <code>Handler</code>. The main thread's looper is created by <code>ActivityThread.main()</code>. This is why UI must happen on the main thread.</p>

  <pre data-lang="Kotlin"><code><span class="cm">// Creating a background thread with a Looper</span>
<span class="kw">val</span> handlerThread = <span class="type">HandlerThread</span>(<span class="str">"my-worker"</span>)
handlerThread.start()
<span class="kw">val</span> handler = <span class="type">Handler</span>(handlerThread.looper) { msg ->
    <span class="cm">// runs on background thread</span>
    <span class="num">true</span>
}

<span class="cm">// Post to main thread from any thread</span>
<span class="type">Handler</span>(<span class="type">Looper</span>.getMainLooper()).post {
    textView.text = <span class="str">"updated"</span>
}

<span class="cm">// In React Native TurboModules, Promises resolve on JS thread via:
// jsCallInvoker->invokeAsync([=]() { resolve(result); });</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Binder IPC — The Android IPC Backbone</h3>
  <p>Binder is Android's kernel-level IPC mechanism. Every system service call (startActivity, getSystemService) goes through Binder. Understanding it explains why main thread work causes ANRs — binder transactions timeout after 5 seconds.</p>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
BINDER IPC FLOW

App Process              Kernel (Binder Driver)       System Server Process
───────────              ──────────────────────       ─────────────────────
Code calls              /dev/binder (ioctl)           ActivityManagerService
startActivity() ──────► BINDER_WRITE_READ ─────────► handles intent
                                                      creates new Activity
                        (return trip)
onActivityResult ◄───── marshalled result ◄─────────  returns

WHY THIS MATTERS FOR ANR:
- If your main thread is blocked and a Binder call comes in
- The system server waits
- After 5s: ANR dialog
- Use Strict Mode to detect main-thread Binder calls
</pre>
  </div>

  <h3>ANR Internals & Debugging</h3>

  <div class="incident">
    <div class="incident-header">
      <span class="incident-badge">Production Incident</span>
      <span class="incident-title">ANR Spike: 2% of users on cold start</span>
    </div>
    <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> ANR in startup. <code>/data/anr/traces.txt</code> showed main thread blocked in <code>SharedPreferences.getAll()</code>.</p>
    <p><strong>Root cause:</strong> RN app loaded large MMKV/SharedPreferences synchronously during <code>ReactNativeHost.getPackages()</code> initialization, which runs on the main thread.</p>
    <p><strong>Fix:</strong> Deferred initialization using <code>lazy</code> + moved to WorkManager pre-fetch. Used <code>DataStore</code> (async) instead of SharedPreferences for large data.</p>
    <p><strong>Tools used:</strong> Android Vitals, Perfetto, <code>adb bugreport</code>, <code>simpleperf</code></p>
  </div>

  <h2>Gradle Deep Dive</h2>

  <h3>Build File Anatomy</h3>

  <pre data-lang="Gradle (Kotlin DSL)"><code><span class="cm">// settings.gradle.kts — project structure</span>
pluginManagement {
    repositories {
        google()
        mavenCentral()
        gradlePluginPortal()
    }
}
dependencyResolutionManagement {
    repositoriesMode.set(<span class="type">RepositoriesMode</span>.FAIL_ON_PROJECT_REPOS)
    repositories {
        google()
        mavenCentral()
        <span class="cm">// RN: node_modules local maven repos</span>
        maven { url = uri(<span class="str">"../node_modules/react-native/android"</span>) }
    }
}
include(<span class="str">":app"</span>)
include(<span class="str">":react-native-camera"</span>) <span class="cm">// auto-linked modules</span>

<span class="cm">// app/build.gradle.kts</span>
android {
    compileSdk = <span class="num">34</span>
    defaultConfig {
        applicationId = <span class="str">"com.myapp"</span>
        minSdk = <span class="num">24</span>
        targetSdk = <span class="num">34</span>
        versionCode = <span class="num">100</span>
        versionName = <span class="str">"1.0.0"</span>
        <span class="cm">// Enable multidex for large RN apps</span>
        multiDexEnabled = <span class="num">true</span>
        <span class="cm">// ABI splits for smaller APK per architecture</span>
        ndk {
            abiFilters += listOf(<span class="str">"arm64-v8a"</span>, <span class="str">"x86_64"</span>)
        }
    }

    buildTypes {
        release {
            isMinifyEnabled = <span class="num">true</span>     <span class="cm">// R8/ProGuard</span>
            isShrinkResources = <span class="num">true</span>  <span class="cm">// remove unused drawables</span>
            proguardFiles(
                getDefaultProguardFile(<span class="str">"proguard-android-optimize.txt"</span>),
                <span class="str">"proguard-rules.pro"</span>
            )
            signingConfig = signingConfigs.getByName(<span class="str">"release"</span>)
        }
        debug {
            applicationIdSuffix = <span class="str">".debug"</span>  <span class="cm">// install both builds</span>
            isDebuggable = <span class="num">true</span>
        }
    }

    productFlavors {
        create(<span class="str">"dev"</span>) {
            dimension = <span class="str">"env"</span>
            applicationIdSuffix = <span class="str">".dev"</span>
            buildConfigField(<span class="str">"String"</span>, <span class="str">"API_URL"</span>, <span class="str">'"https://dev.api.com"'</span>)
        }
        create(<span class="str">"prod"</span>) {
            dimension = <span class="str">"env"</span>
            buildConfigField(<span class="str">"String"</span>, <span class="str">"API_URL"</span>, <span class="str">'"https://api.com"'</span>)
        }
    }
}</code></pre>

  <h3>APK vs AAB: Why This Matters</h3>

  <div class="diff-grid">
    <div class="diff-col good">
      <div class="diff-label">✓ AAB (Android App Bundle) — Recommended</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Upload to Play Store, Google generates optimized APKs per device</li>
        <li>~15–25% smaller download for users</li>
        <li>Required for Play Store since August 2021</li>
        <li>Supports dynamic delivery, on-demand features</li>
        <li>Device-specific: correct language, density, ABI</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="diff-col bad">
      <div class="diff-label">↓ APK — Direct Install Only</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Universal APK includes all ABIs, densities</li>
        <li>Larger file size</li>
        <li>Use for enterprise sideloading, CI testing</li>
        <li>Still needed for Firebase App Distribution</li>
        <li>Can generate split APKs manually with bundletool</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>R8 / ProGuard — What RN Engineers Must Know</h3>
  <pre data-lang="ProGuard"><code><span class="cm"># Keep RN bridge classes</span>
-keep <span class="kw">class</span> com.facebook.react.** { *; }
-keep <span class="kw">class</span> com.facebook.hermes.** { *; }
-keep <span class="kw">class</span> com.facebook.jni.** { *; }

<span class="cm"># Keep your native module classes</span>
-keep <span class="kw">class</span> com.myapp.modules.** { *; }

<span class="cm"># Keep enums (commonly forgotten)</span>
-keepclassmembers <span class="kw">enum</span> * {
    <span class="kw">public static</span> **[] values();
    <span class="kw">public static</span> ** valueOf(java.lang.String);
}

<span class="cm"># Prevent stripping Kotlin metadata</span>
-keep <span class="kw">class</span> kotlin.Metadata { *; }
-keepattributes RuntimeVisibleAnnotations</code></pre>

  <div class="callout callout-warn">
    <span class="callout-icon">⚡</span>
    <div class="callout-content">
      <div class="callout-title">R8 Gotcha in Production</div>
      R8 with full mode aggressively removes classes it thinks are unused. In RN, TurboModule codegen classes and JSI C++ native code are loaded via reflection/JNI — R8 doesn't see these references. Always verify your keep rules with <code>./gradlew :app:generateReleaseR8Usage</code> and test release builds on real devices before shipping.
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Multidex & Dexing</h3>
  <p>Android's Dalvik/ART limits a single DEX file to 65,536 method references (the "64K limit"). Large RN apps with many node_modules routinely exceed this. <code>multiDexEnabled = true</code> splits into multiple DEX files. On API 21+ this is handled natively. Below API 21 requires the multidex support library.</p>

  <h3>Gradle Performance Optimization</h3>
  <pre data-lang="gradle.properties"><code><span class="cm"># Memory</span>
org.gradle.jvmargs=-Xmx4g -XX:+UseParallelGC

<span class="cm"># Parallel execution</span>
org.gradle.parallel=true
org.gradle.caching=true

<span class="cm"># Configuration cache (Gradle 8+)</span>
org.gradle.configuration-cache=true

<span class="cm"># Incremental kotlin compilation</span>
kotlin.incremental=true
kotlin.incremental.useClasspathSnapshot=true

<span class="cm"># RN specific</span>
FLIPPER_VERSION=0.182.0
newArchEnabled=true
hermesEnabled=true</code></pre>

  <h2>Kotlin for RN Engineers</h2>

  <h3>Coroutines — Deep Dive</h3>
  <p>Coroutines are not threads. They are <em>suspendable computations</em> — code that can pause without blocking a thread, resume later on any thread, and handle cancellation cooperatively.</p>

  <pre data-lang="Kotlin"><code><span class="cm">// Structured Concurrency: coroutines have parent-child relationships</span>
<span class="kw">class</span> <span class="type">MyTurboModule</span>(reactContext: <span class="type">ReactApplicationContext</span>) :
    <span class="type">NativeMyModuleSpec</span>(reactContext) {

    <span class="cm">// Module scope: cancelled when module is torn down</span>
    <span class="kw">private val</span> scope = <span class="type">CoroutineScope</span>(<span class="type">SupervisorJob</span>() + <span class="type">Dispatchers</span>.IO)

    <span class="kw">override fun</span> <span class="fn">fetchData</span>(promise: <span class="type">Promise</span>) {
        scope.launch {
            <span class="kw">try</span> {
                <span class="kw">val</span> result = withContext(<span class="type">Dispatchers</span>.IO) {
                    networkClient.get(<span class="str">"/data"</span>)  <span class="cm">// suspending</span>
                }
                <span class="cm">// Switch to JS thread to resolve</span>
                promise.resolve(result.toWritableMap())
            } <span class="kw">catch</span> (e: <span class="type">CancellationException</span>) {
                <span class="cm">// Don't catch CancellationException! Re-throw it</span>
                <span class="kw">throw</span> e
            } <span class="kw">catch</span> (e: <span class="type">Exception</span>) {
                promise.reject(<span class="str">"FETCH_ERROR"</span>, e.message, e)
            }
        }
    }

    <span class="kw">override fun</span> <span class="fn">invalidate</span>() {
        scope.cancel() <span class="cm">// cancel all pending coroutines</span>
        <span class="kw">super</span>.invalidate()
    }
}

<span class="cm">// Flows for streaming data (e.g., BLE sensor data to RN)</span>
<span class="kw">private val</span> sensorFlow: <span class="type">SharedFlow</span>&lt;<span class="type">SensorData</span>&gt; = bleScanner
    .scan()
    .conflate()   <span class="cm">// drop old values if JS can't keep up</span>
    .shareIn(scope, <span class="type">SharingStarted</span>.WhileSubscribed(<span class="num">5000</span>), replay = <span class="num">1</span>)</code></pre>

  <h3>Dispatchers Explained</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Dispatcher</th><th>Thread Pool</th><th>Use Case</th><th>RN Use</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Dispatchers.Main</td><td>UI thread</td><td>UI updates, View manipulation</td><td>Emit events to RN bridge</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Dispatchers.IO</td><td>64 threads max</td><td>Network, disk, DB</td><td>TurboModule network calls</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Dispatchers.Default</td><td>CPU core count</td><td>CPU-intensive computation</td><td>Image processing, crypto</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Dispatchers.Unconfined</td><td>Caller thread</td><td>Testing, special cases</td><td>Unit test mocking</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2>JNI & C++ for RN Engineers</h2>

  <p>React Native's JSI uses C++ and JNI extensively. Understanding this unlocks the ability to build performant TurboModules and debug native crashes.</p>

  <pre data-lang="C++"><code><span class="cm">// JSI Host Object: exposes C++ object directly to JavaScript</span>
<span class="kw">class</span> <span class="type">NativeCryptoModule</span> : <span class="kw">public</span> jsi::<span class="type">HostObject</span> {
<span class="kw">public</span>:
  jsi::<span class="type">Value</span> <span class="fn">get</span>(jsi::<span class="type">Runtime</span>& rt, <span class="kw">const</span> jsi::<span class="type">PropNameID</span>& name) <span class="kw">override</span> {
    <span class="kw">auto</span> propName = name.utf8(rt);

    <span class="kw">if</span> (propName == <span class="str">"hash"</span>) {
      <span class="kw">return</span> jsi::<span class="type">Function</span>::createFromHostFunction(
        rt, jsi::<span class="type">PropNameID</span>::forUtf8(rt, <span class="str">"hash"</span>), <span class="num">1</span>,
        [](jsi::<span class="type">Runtime</span>& rt, <span class="kw">const</span> jsi::<span class="type">Value</span>&,
           <span class="kw">const</span> jsi::<span class="type">Value</span>* args, size_t) -> jsi::<span class="type">Value</span> {
          <span class="kw">auto</span> input = args[<span class="num">0</span>].asString(rt).utf8(rt);
          <span class="cm">// Direct C++ computation — zero serialization overhead</span>
          <span class="kw">return</span> jsi::<span class="type">String</span>::createFromUtf8(rt, sha256(input));
        }
      );
    }
    <span class="kw">return</span> jsi::<span class="type">Value</span>::undefined();
  }
};

<span class="cm">// Register via JNI</span>
<span class="kw">extern</span> <span class="str">"C"</span> JNIEXPORT <span class="type">void</span> JNICALL
<span class="type">Java_com_myapp_NativeCryptoModule_install</span>(<span class="type">JNIEnv</span>* env, jobject, jlong jsRuntime) {
  <span class="kw">auto</span>& rt = *<span class="kw">reinterpret_cast</span>&lt;jsi::<span class="type">Runtime</span>*&gt;(jsRuntime);
  <span class="kw">auto</span> module = std::make_shared&lt;<span class="type">NativeCryptoModule</span>&gt;();
  rt.global().setProperty(rt, <span class="str">"NativeCrypto"</span>,
    jsi::<span class="type">Object</span>::createFromHostObject(rt, module));
}</code></pre>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <span class="callout-icon">🔍</span>
    <div class="callout-content">
      <div class="callout-title">Debugging Native Crashes (tombstones)</div>
      When C++/JNI code crashes, Android generates a tombstone in <code>/data/tombstones/</code>. Use <code>ndk-stack</code> to symbolicate: <code>adb logcat | ndk-stack -sym ./app/build/intermediates/cmake/debug/obj/arm64-v8a</code>. For Hermes crashes, use the <code>.map</code> file from your Hermes build to map bytecode offsets.
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Android Performance Profiling</h2>

  <h3>Perfetto — The Modern Profiler</h3>
  <pre data-lang="bash"><code><span class="cm"># Record system trace</span>
adb shell perfetto \
  -c - --txt \
  -o /data/misc/perfetto-traces/trace.pftrace \
  &lt;&lt; EOF
buffers: { size_kb: 63488 fill_policy: RING_BUFFER }
data_sources: { config { name: "linux.ftrace"
  ftrace_config { ftrace_events: "sched/sched_switch"
    ftrace_events: "power/suspend_resume"
    atrace_categories: "gfx" atrace_categories: "view"
    atrace_apps: "com.myapp" } } }
duration_ms: 10000
EOF

<span class="cm"># Open at ui.perfetto.dev</span>
adb pull /data/misc/perfetto-traces/trace.pftrace</code></pre>

  <h3>Choreographer and Frame Rendering</h3>
  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
ANDROID FRAME RENDERING PIPELINE (60fps = 16ms budget)

VSync Signal (16ms)
      │
      ▼
Choreographer.doFrame()
      │
      ├─► Input callbacks       (~1ms)
      ├─► Animation callbacks   (~2ms)
      ├─► Traversal callbacks
      │     ├─ measure()        (~3ms)
      │     ├─ layout()         (~2ms)
      │     └─ draw()           (~4ms) → DisplayList
      │
      ▼
RenderThread (hardware acceleration)
      ├─ Sync frame
      ├─ Upload textures
      └─ Issue GL/Vulkan commands → GPU
            │
            ▼
        Display Buffer Swap → Screen
</pre>
  </div>

  <div class="iq-box">
    <div class="iq-header">
      <span class="iq-label">Interview Question</span>
      <span class="iq-level lvl-staff">Staff Level</span>
    </div>
    <div class="iq-q">Explain how a React Native touch event on Android travels from the screen to a JS event handler. What can go wrong at each stage?</div>
    <div class="iq-a">
      <strong>Answer:</strong> The touch pipeline:
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Hardware → InputReader (kernel)</strong>: Raw touch coords arrive from touchscreen driver via <code>/dev/input</code></li>
        <li><strong>InputDispatcher</strong>: Routes to the focused window (your Activity). If main thread is blocked &gt;5s, ANR.</li>
        <li><strong>ReactRootView.onTouchEvent()</strong>: On Main Thread. Creates a ReactPointerEventsMap, dispatches to JSTouchDispatcher.</li>
        <li><strong>Old Arch</strong>: Serialized to JSON, queued on bridge, sent to JS thread asynchronously — ~1-2 frame delay.</li>
        <li><strong>New Arch (Fabric)</strong>: Touch is handled synchronously on UI thread via C++ event emitter, JSI call on JS thread — &lt;1 frame latency.</li>
        <li><strong>JS</strong>: React synthetic event system, bubbling, handler execution.</li>
      </ol>
      <strong>What goes wrong:</strong> Main thread jank blocks input. Long JS frame delays touch response. Fabric fixes this with synchronous event dispatch.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="iq-box">
    <div class="iq-header">
      <span class="iq-label">Interview Question</span>
      <span class="iq-level lvl-faang">FAANG Level</span>
    </div>
    <div class="iq-q">Your Android app has a 3% crash-free session rate regression after a Gradle upgrade. Walk through your investigation.</div>
    <div class="iq-a">
      <strong>Answer:</strong>
      <ol>
        <li>Check Firebase Crashlytics: group crashes by type. Is it a native crash (signal 11) or Java exception?</li>
        <li>Compare R8/ProGuard rules between versions. Gradle upgrades often bump R8 version → more aggressive optimization → missing keep rules.</li>
        <li>Check <code>mapping.txt</code> in Firebase to deobfuscate stack traces.</li>
        <li>Run <code>./gradlew :app:generateReleaseR8Usage</code> to see what R8 is removing.</li>
        <li>If native crash: check NDK version bump. Different NDK versions have different C++ STL ABIs.</li>
        <li>Bisect: revert Gradle version, confirm regression disappears, then add back incrementally.</li>
        <li>Write regression test: CI step that verifies crash-free rate on Firebase Test Lab before merge.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>

</section>

<!-- ===== SECTION 2: iOS ===== -->
<section class="section" id="ios">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-num">02</div>
    <div class="section-title-wrap">
      <div class="section-tag">Native Platform Deep Dive</div>
      <h1 class="section-title">iOS Native Engineering</h1>
      <p class="section-desc">UIKit internals, Swift concurrency, ARC memory model, how Fabric integrates into UIKit, and production iOS debugging workflows.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="tags">
    <span class="badge badge-ios">iOS</span>
    <span class="tag">Swift</span>
    <span class="tag">ARC</span>
    <span class="tag">RunLoop</span>
    <span class="tag">GCD</span>
    <span class="tag">Instruments</span>
    <span class="tag">Fabric</span>
  </div>

  <h2>UIApplication & App Delegate Lifecycle</h2>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
iOS APP LIFECYCLE

  Not Running
      │
      ▼ launch
  Inactive ──── (scene connected) ──► Active
      │                                   │
      │ (interrupt: call, siri, etc)       │
      ◄──────────────────────────────────-┘
      │
      ▼ (home button / swipe up)
  Background ──── (suspend) ──► Suspended
      │                              │
      │ (background task time expires)│
      ▼                              │
  Terminated ◄────────────────────-─┘
  (SIGKILL from OS)

UIApplicationDelegate (per process):
  - application(_:didFinishLaunchingWithOptions:) → RN bridge starts here
  - applicationWillResignActive / applicationDidBecomeActive
  - applicationDidEnterBackground → AppState 'background'
  - applicationWillEnterForeground → AppState 'active'
  - applicationWillTerminate → cleanup

SceneDelegate (iOS 13+, per window):
  - scene(_:willConnectTo:) → attach UI
  - sceneDidBecomeActive
  - sceneWillResignActive
  - sceneDidEnterBackground
</pre>
  </div>

  <h3>AppDelegate vs SceneDelegate in React Native</h3>
  <p>React Native's template uses <code>AppDelegate</code> directly. However, iPad multitasking and split-screen require <code>SceneDelegate</code>. For RN apps supporting iPad, you must initialize <code>RCTBridge</code> per scene, not per app.</p>

  <pre data-lang="Swift"><code><span class="ann">@main</span>
<span class="kw">class</span> <span class="type">AppDelegate</span>: <span class="type">UIResponder</span>, <span class="type">UIApplicationDelegate</span> {

    <span class="kw">var</span> bridge: <span class="type">RCTBridge</span>?

    <span class="kw">func</span> <span class="fn">application</span>(
        _ application: <span class="type">UIApplication</span>,
        didFinishLaunchingWithOptions launchOptions: [<span class="type">UIApplication.LaunchOptionsKey</span>: <span class="type">Any</span>]?
    ) -> <span class="type">Bool</span> {

        <span class="cm">// New Architecture: RCTAppSetupUtils</span>
        <span class="type">RCTAppSetupPrepareApp</span>(application, turboModuleEnabled: <span class="num">true</span>)

        <span class="kw">let</span> bridge = <span class="type">RCTBridge</span>(delegate: <span class="kw">self</span>, launchOptions: launchOptions)

        <span class="cm">// Fabric + Concurrent React</span>
        <span class="kw">let</span> rootView = <span class="type">RCTFabricSurfaceHostingProxyRootView</span>(
            bridge: bridge,
            moduleName: <span class="str">"MyApp"</span>,
            initialProperties: [:]
        )

        <span class="kw">let</span> rootVC = <span class="type">UIViewController</span>()
        rootVC.view = rootView
        window = <span class="type">UIWindow</span>(frame: <span class="type">UIScreen</span>.main.bounds)
        window?.rootViewController = rootVC
        window?.makeKeyAndVisible()

        <span class="kw">return true</span>
    }
}

<span class="kw">extension</span> <span class="type">AppDelegate</span>: <span class="type">RCTBridgeDelegate</span> {
    <span class="kw">func</span> <span class="fn">sourceURL</span>(<span class="kw">for</span> bridge: <span class="type">RCTBridge</span>!) -> <span class="type">URL</span>! {
        <span class="cm">// Dev: Metro server. Release: bundle in app</span>
        <span class="kw">#if</span> DEBUG
        <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="type">RCTBundleURLProvider</span>.sharedSettings().jsBundleURL(
            forBundleRoot: <span class="str">"index"</span>)
        <span class="kw">#else</span>
        <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="type">Bundle</span>.main.url(forResource: <span class="str">"main"</span>, withExtension: <span class="str">"jsbundle"</span>)
        <span class="kw">#endif</span>
    }
}</code></pre>

  <h2>ARC Memory Management</h2>

  <h3>How ARC Works Internally</h3>
  <p>ARC (Automatic Reference Counting) inserts <code>retain</code>/<code>release</code> calls at compile time — it's not a garbage collector. Objects are freed immediately when their retain count hits zero. This means <em>deterministic deallocation</em> but requires developer awareness of retain cycles.</p>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
RETAIN CYCLE (Memory Leak Pattern)

  ViewController ──strong──► ViewModel
       ▲                         │
       └─────────strong───────────┘
                  (cycle!)

  FIX: Use [weak self] or [unowned self]

  class ViewModel {
      var onUpdate: (() -> Void)?  // strong

      func bind(to vc: ViewController) {
          onUpdate = { [weak vc] in   // weak — no cycle
              vc?.updateUI()
          }
      }
  }

REACT NATIVE RETAIN CYCLE PATTERN:
  RCTBridge ──strong──► NativeModule
  NativeModule ──strong──► closure with self
                            self has reference back → LEAK

  FIX: In RCTEventEmitter subclasses, always use
  [weak self] in async callbacks to bridge
</pre>
  </div>

  <pre data-lang="Swift"><code><span class="cm">// Common RN memory leak: strong capture in async callback</span>
<span class="kw">class</span> <span class="type">MyNativeModule</span>: <span class="type">NSObject</span>, <span class="type">RCTBridgeModule</span> {

    <span class="cm">// BAD: strong self capture → retain cycle with bridge</span>
    <span class="kw">func</span> <span class="fn">badFetch</span>(_ resolve: <span class="ann">@escaping</span> <span class="type">RCTPromiseResolveBlock</span>) {
        <span class="type">URLSession</span>.shared.dataTask(with: url) { data, _, _ <span class="kw">in</span>
            <span class="kw">self</span>.process(data)  <span class="cm">// strong capture!</span>
            resolve(result)
        }.resume()
    }

    <span class="cm">// GOOD: weak self, guard let to safely unwrap</span>
    <span class="kw">func</span> <span class="fn">goodFetch</span>(_ resolve: <span class="ann">@escaping</span> <span class="type">RCTPromiseResolveBlock</span>) {
        <span class="type">URLSession</span>.shared.dataTask(with: url) { [<span class="kw">weak self</span>] data, _, _ <span class="kw">in</span>
            <span class="kw">guard let self</span> <span class="kw">else</span> { <span class="kw">return</span> } <span class="cm">// Swift 5.3+</span>
            <span class="kw">self</span>.process(data)
            resolve(result)
        }.resume()
    }
}</code></pre>

  <h2>GCD & Swift Concurrency</h2>

  <h3>Grand Central Dispatch — The Foundation</h3>
  <pre data-lang="Swift"><code><span class="cm">// GCD Queue types</span>
<span class="type">DispatchQueue</span>.main  <span class="cm">// Serial, UI thread</span>
<span class="type">DispatchQueue</span>.global(qos: .userInteractive)  <span class="cm">// Concurrent, highest priority</span>
<span class="type">DispatchQueue</span>.global(qos: .background)       <span class="cm">// Concurrent, lowest priority</span>

<span class="cm">// Custom serial queue (ordered operations)</span>
<span class="kw">let</span> serialQ = <span class="type">DispatchQueue</span>(label: <span class="str">"com.myapp.serial"</span>)

<span class="cm">// DispatchGroup for parallel work + completion</span>
<span class="kw">let</span> group = <span class="type">DispatchGroup</span>()
group.enter(); fetchProfile { group.leave() }
group.enter(); fetchFeed    { group.leave() }
group.notify(queue: .main) { [<span class="kw">weak self</span>] <span class="kw">in</span>
    <span class="kw">self</span>?.renderDashboard()
}

<span class="cm">// Deadlock: NEVER dispatch_sync on same queue you're on</span>
<span class="type">DispatchQueue</span>.main.sync { } <span class="cm">// on main thread → DEADLOCK</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Swift Concurrency (async/await)</h3>
  <pre data-lang="Swift"><code><span class="cm">// Actor: thread-safe isolated state</span>
<span class="kw">actor</span> <span class="type">DataCache</span> {
    <span class="kw">private var</span> store: [<span class="type">String</span>: <span class="type">Data</span>] = [:]

    <span class="kw">func</span> <span class="fn">store</span>(_ data: <span class="type">Data</span>, key: <span class="type">String</span>) {
        store[key] = data  <span class="cm">// safe, actor-isolated</span>
    }

    <span class="kw">func</span> <span class="fn">get</span>(key: <span class="type">String</span>) -> <span class="type">Data</span>? { store[key] }
}

<span class="cm">// MainActor: runs on main thread (replaces DispatchQueue.main)</span>
<span class="ann">@MainActor</span>
<span class="kw">class</span> <span class="type">ViewModel</span>: <span class="type">ObservableObject</span> {
    <span class="ann">@Published</span> <span class="kw">var</span> items: [<span class="type">Item</span>] = []

    <span class="kw">func</span> <span class="fn">load</span>() <span class="kw">async</span> {
        <span class="kw">let</span> result = <span class="kw">await</span> networkService.fetch()  <span class="cm">// off main</span>
        items = result  <span class="cm">// back on main (MainActor)</span>
    }
}

<span class="cm">// Task cancellation — critical for NativeModules</span>
<span class="kw">func</span> <span class="fn">fetchWithCancellation</span>() -> <span class="type">Task</span>&lt;<span class="type">Data</span>, <span class="type">Error</span>&gt; {
    <span class="type">Task</span> {
        <span class="kw">try</span> <span class="type">Task</span>.checkCancellation()  <span class="cm">// throw if cancelled</span>
        <span class="kw">let</span> data = <span class="kw">try await</span> URLSession.shared.data(from: url)
        <span class="kw">try</span> <span class="type">Task</span>.checkCancellation()  <span class="cm">// check again after await</span>
        <span class="kw">return</span> data.0
    }
}</code></pre>

  <h2>RunLoop Internals</h2>
  <p>The iOS RunLoop is conceptually identical to Android's <code>Looper</code>. It's an event-processing loop on a thread. React Native's JS thread has its own RunLoop managed by the bridge. Understanding RunLoop explains why timers, CADisplayLink, and network callbacks all need one.</p>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
iOS RunLoop Lifecycle

  RunLoop.run()
      │
      ├─ Check timer sources (NSTimer, CADisplayLink)
      ├─ Check input sources (port messages, touches)
      ├─ Process pending blocks (dispatch_async to same thread)
      ├─ Check observers (kCFRunLoopBeforeTimers, AfterWaiting, etc.)
      └─ Sleep (waiting for events)
           │
           └─ Wake on: new event, timer fire, source signal

React Native Bridge: JSExecutor runs on its own thread with a RunLoop.
Metro bundle load uses RunLoop to process incoming URL data.
CADisplayLink (60hz timer) powers Reanimated's animation driver.
</pre>
  </div>

  <h2>How Fabric Mounts Into UIKit</h2>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
FABRIC RENDERING PIPELINE (New Architecture)

JavaScript Thread
  │  React renders → Fiber tree update
  │  Shadow tree mutations generated
  ▼
Fabric C++ Renderer (JSI, no bridge serialization)
  │  Calculates layout via Yoga (C++)
  │  Creates "committed" shadow tree
  ▼
Main Thread (UIKit)
  │  Shadow tree → UIView hierarchy
  │  Each RN component → custom UIView subclass
  │  Synchronous mount → no async delay
  ▼
UIView hierarchy ← committed synchronously
  │
  ▼
CALayer → Core Animation → GPU → Display

KEY IMPROVEMENT over Old Bridge:
- No JSON serialization between JS and native
- Shadow tree operations in C++ (not ObjC)
- Synchronous layout for useLayoutEffect
- Concurrent Mode: partial renders without blocking UI
</pre>
  </div>

  <h2>Provisioning, Signing & Certificates</h2>

  <div class="card-grid">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-icon">🔑</div>
      <div class="card-title">Distribution Certificate</div>
      <div class="card-body">Private key (.p12) on your Mac. Signs the code. Team can only have 3. If you lose the private key, revoke and create a new one — this invalidates existing builds. Store in CI as base64 secret.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-icon">📄</div>
      <div class="card-title">Provisioning Profile</div>
      <div class="card-body">Links: App ID + Certificate + Devices. App Store profiles don't list devices. Ad Hoc lists specific UDIDs. Development profiles needed for on-device debugging. Match (Fastlane) automates this entire mess.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-icon">🆔</div>
      <div class="card-title">App ID / Bundle ID</div>
      <div class="card-body">com.company.app format. Wildcards (com.company.*) for testing. Explicit App IDs required for push notifications, In-App Purchase, App Clips. Each capability (push, wallet, etc.) must be enabled in App ID and provisioning profile.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-icon">⚡</div>
      <div class="card-title">Fastlane Match — The Solution</div>
      <div class="card-body">Stores encrypted certs in Git or S3. Team members run <code>fastlane match appstore</code> to sync. CI uses readonly mode. Eliminates cert rotation hell. Strongly recommended for any team &gt;2 iOS devs.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>APNs — Push Notifications Internals</h2>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
APNs DELIVERY PIPELINE

Your Server                APNs                  Device
──────────                 ────                  ──────
  POST /3/device/{token} ──HTTP/2──► APNs servers
  Headers: apns-topic,               │
           apns-priority              │ TCP persistent
           apns-expiration            │ connection
           authorization: bearer JWT  │
                                      ▼
                                 Device wakes
                                 (even from sleep)
                                      │
                                      ▼
                                 iOS delivers to app
                                 application(_:didReceiveRemoteNotification:)
                                 OR background fetch if content-available:1

TOKENS:
- Environment-specific (dev token ≠ prod token)
- Rotate after app reinstall → your server must handle 410 Gone
- Silent notifications (content-available): ~30min delivery guarantee
- User-visible notifications: near-realtime
</pre>
  </div>

  <h2>iOS Performance & Instruments</h2>

  <h3>Instruments Workflows for RN Engineers</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Instrument</th><th>What It Finds</th><th>RN Use Case</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Allocations</td><td>Object creation, memory leaks</td><td>Find leaking native modules, ViewManagers</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Leaks</td><td>Retain cycles automatically</td><td>Confirm strong→weak fix worked</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Time Profiler</td><td>CPU hotspots by function</td><td>Find expensive ObjC bridge calls</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Core Animation</td><td>Frame rate, off-screen rendering</td><td>Identify GPU overdraw in complex lists</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Network</td><td>HTTP timing, size, caching</td><td>Debug slow image loads, missing cache headers</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Energy Log</td><td>CPU/GPU/Radio/Location usage</td><td>Battery drain from background location</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="iq-box">
    <div class="iq-header">
      <span class="iq-label">Interview Question</span>
      <span class="iq-level lvl-staff">Staff Level</span>
    </div>
    <div class="iq-q">How does React Native integrate with the iOS RunLoop, and how does this affect timer accuracy in Reanimated?</div>
    <div class="iq-a">
      <strong>Answer:</strong> React Native creates a dedicated JS thread with its own <code>CFRunLoop</code>. The <code>RCTJSThread</code> is started during bridge initialization. JavaScript timers (<code>setTimeout</code>) are implemented as <code>NSTimer</code> callbacks on this RunLoop.
      <br><br>
      Reanimated v3+ bypasses this entirely: it uses <code>CADisplayLink</code> on the main thread (or a dedicated animation thread) synchronized to the display's vsync signal (60/120Hz). This gives frame-accurate animation timing vs the ±16ms jitter of RunLoop-based timers. The worklets run in a separate JS runtime context with its own RunLoop, isolated from the main JS bundle.
      <br><br>
      <strong>Implication:</strong> Don't use <code>setInterval</code> for animations. Always use Reanimated or Animated (which internally also uses the display sync path on iOS).
    </div>
  </div>

</section>

<!-- ===== SECTION 3: REACT INTERNALS ===== -->
<section class="section" id="react">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-num">03</div>
    <div class="section-title-wrap">
      <div class="section-tag">Framework Internals</div>
      <h1 class="section-title">React Internals</h1>
      <p class="section-desc">Fiber architecture, reconciliation, concurrent rendering, React 19, Suspense, and how React Native uses Fiber internally.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="tags">
    <span class="badge badge-rn">React</span>
    <span class="tag">Fiber</span>
    <span class="tag">Concurrent Mode</span>
    <span class="tag">Suspense</span>
    <span class="tag">React 19</span>
    <span class="tag">Scheduler</span>
  </div>

  <h2>Fiber Architecture — First Principles</h2>

  <p>Before Fiber (React 15 and earlier), reconciliation was synchronous and recursive. Once React started processing an update, it couldn't stop until the entire tree was processed. On complex trees, this caused dropped frames.</p>

  <p>Fiber (React 16+) rewrites reconciliation as an <em>interruptible, incremental</em> work loop. Each component becomes a "fiber" — a unit of work that can be paused, resumed, prioritized, or discarded.</p>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
FIBER DATA STRUCTURE

Each Fiber is a plain JS object:
{
  type:        Button          // component type
  key:         null
  stateNode:   DOM/Native node // actual rendered node
  return:      parentFiber     // parent
  child:       firstChildFiber // first child
  sibling:     nextSibling     // next sibling
  alternate:   workInProgress  // double buffering twin
  flags:       Update | Placement | Deletion
  lanes:       0b00010         // priority lane
  memoizedState: { hook linked list }
  pendingProps:  { ... }
  memoizedProps: { ... }
  updateQueue:  { pending updates }
}

FIBER TREE TRAVERSAL (DFS):
  parent
    │
    ├── child1  ← child
    │     └── child1.1 ← child
    └── child2  ← sibling

Order: parent → child1 → child1.1 → child2
</pre>
  </div>

  <h3>Reconciliation: Render Phase vs Commit Phase</h3>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
REACT RENDER LIFECYCLE

═══════════════ RENDER PHASE (interruptible) ═══════════════
  │
  ├─ beginWork(fiber)
  │   ├─ Determine if component needs re-render
  │   ├─ Call render/function body
  │   ├─ Diff children (reconcileChildFibers)
  │   └─ Return child fiber to process next
  │
  ├─ completeWork(fiber)
  │   ├─ Create/update host instances (View, Text)
  │   ├─ Collect effects
  │   └─ Return to parent
  │
  ├─ [INTERRUPTIBLE: Scheduler can pause here]
  │   Higher priority update? → discard work, restart
  │
═══════════════ COMMIT PHASE (synchronous) ══════════════════
  │
  ├─ Before Mutation:  getSnapshotBeforeUpdate
  ├─ Mutation:         DOM/Native mutations, ref detach
  ├─ Layout:           useLayoutEffect, componentDidMount/Update
  │                    (synchronous — before browser paint)
  └─ Passive:          useEffect (deferred, after paint)
                       scheduled via MessageChannel (macrotask)
</pre>
  </div>

  <h3>Lanes — Priority System</h3>
  <pre data-lang="JavaScript"><code><span class="cm">// React 18 Lane priorities (simplified)</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> <span class="type">SyncLane</span>          = <span class="num">0b0000000000000000000000000000001</span>; <span class="cm">// user input</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> <span class="type">InputContinuousLane</span>= <span class="num">0b0000000000000000000000000000100</span>; <span class="cm">// scroll</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> <span class="type">DefaultLane</span>       = <span class="num">0b0000000000000000000000000010000</span>; <span class="cm">// setState</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> <span class="type">TransitionLane1</span>   = <span class="num">0b0000000000000000000001000000000</span>; <span class="cm">// startTransition</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> <span class="type">IdleLane</span>          = <span class="num">0b0100000000000000000000000000000</span>; <span class="cm">// background work</span>

<span class="cm">// startTransition: marks updates as non-urgent</span>
<span class="kw">import</span> { startTransition, useTransition } <span class="kw">from</span> <span class="str">'react'</span>;

<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">SearchResults</span>() {
  <span class="kw">const</span> [query, setQuery] = useState(<span class="str">''</span>);
  <span class="kw">const</span> [results, setResults] = useState([]);
  <span class="kw">const</span> [isPending, startTransition] = useTransition();

  <span class="kw">return</span> (
    &lt;TextInput
      onChangeText={(text) => {
        setQuery(text);  <span class="cm">// SyncLane — immediate, keeps input responsive</span>
        startTransition(() => {
          setResults(search(text));  <span class="cm">// TransitionLane — interruptible</span>
        });
      }}
    /&gt;
  );
}</code></pre>

  <h3>Automatic Batching (React 18)</h3>
  <p>Before React 18, only event handlers had batching. Async callbacks (<code>setTimeout</code>, Promises, native event handlers) triggered re-renders per <code>setState</code>.</p>
  <pre data-lang="JavaScript"><code><span class="cm">// React 17 — 2 re-renders (async context)</span>
setTimeout(() => {
  setA(<span class="num">1</span>); <span class="cm">// re-render</span>
  setB(<span class="num">2</span>); <span class="cm">// re-render</span>
}, <span class="num">100</span>);

<span class="cm">// React 18 — 1 re-render (automatic batching)</span>
setTimeout(() => {
  setA(<span class="num">1</span>); <span class="cm">// batched</span>
  setB(<span class="num">2</span>); <span class="cm">// batched → single re-render</span>
}, <span class="num">100</span>);

<span class="cm">// Opt out with flushSync (rare, layout measurements)</span>
<span class="kw">import</span> { flushSync } <span class="kw">from</span> <span class="str">'react-dom'</span>;
flushSync(() => setA(<span class="num">1</span>)); <span class="cm">// forces immediate render</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Suspense Internals</h3>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
SUSPENSE MECHANICS

  &lt;Suspense fallback={&lt;Spinner /&gt;}&gt;
    &lt;LazyComponent /&gt;  ← throws Promise (Thenables)
  &lt;/Suspense&gt;

Internal flow:
  1. LazyComponent renders
  2. Throws a Promise (or use() hook in React 19)
  3. React catches the throw in renderWithHooks()
  4. Walks up fiber tree to nearest Suspense boundary
  5. Attaches .then() callback to the Promise
  6. Renders fallback immediately
  7. When Promise resolves → re-renders LazyComponent

CONCURRENT MODE BENEFIT:
  Old: Suspense blocked entire tree
  New: React can render other subtrees while waiting
       Multiple data fetches → waterfall eliminated
       use() in React 19: integrates with cache
</pre>
  </div>

  <h3>React 19 Key Changes</h3>

  <div class="card-grid">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">use() Hook</div>
      <div class="card-body">Reads values from Promises and Context synchronously. Works inside conditions and loops. Replaces useContext + data fetching boilerplate. Integrates with Suspense automatically.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">Server Actions</div>
      <div class="card-body">Mark async functions with "use server" to run on server. RN relevance: React Native Server Components (Expo RSC) use this pattern for data loading. Reduces bundle size by keeping logic off-device.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">React Compiler</div>
      <div class="card-body">Automatically memoizes components and hooks — no manual useMemo/useCallback. Analyzes code statically, inserts optimal memoization. Significant performance improvement for RN without code changes.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">ref as Prop</div>
      <div class="card-body">No more forwardRef boilerplate. Refs passed as regular props. Simplifies native component wrappers in RN. Combined with useImperativeHandle for custom handle APIs.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>useEffect vs useLayoutEffect — When They Fire</h3>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
TIMING: useEffect vs useLayoutEffect

  React renders → commits mutations to native
                │
                ▼
         useLayoutEffect fires   ← SYNCHRONOUS
         (before paint, blocks paint)
         → safe to read layout, measure views
         → sets up animations before first paint
                │
                ▼
         [Platform paints frame to screen]
                │
                ▼
         useEffect fires         ← ASYNCHRONOUS
         (after paint, scheduled as macrotask)
         → data fetching, subscriptions, logging
         → mutating DOM here causes extra paint

In React Native:
  useLayoutEffect → fires after Fabric commit, before view drawn
  useEffect → fires after JS frame, may cause visible flicker if measuring views
</pre>
  </div>

  <h3>Stale Closures — The Most Common React Bug</h3>
  <pre data-lang="JavaScript"><code><span class="cm">// Stale closure: count is captured at creation time</span>
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">Counter</span>() {
  <span class="kw">const</span> [count, setCount] = useState(<span class="num">0</span>);

  useEffect(() => {
    <span class="kw">const</span> timer = setInterval(() => {
      console.log(count); <span class="cm">// ALWAYS prints 0! Stale closure</span>
      setCount(count + <span class="num">1</span>); <span class="cm">// WRONG: count is stale</span>
    }, <span class="num">1000</span>);
    <span class="kw">return</span> () => clearInterval(timer);
  }, []); <span class="cm">// empty deps — closure captured count=0 forever</span>
}

<span class="cm">// FIX 1: Add count to deps (new effect per render)</span>
useEffect(() => { ... }, [count]);

<span class="cm">// FIX 2: Functional update (doesn't need current value in closure)</span>
setCount(prev => prev + <span class="num">1</span>); <span class="cm">// prev is always fresh</span>

<span class="cm">// FIX 3: useRef for mutable value not tied to render</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> countRef = useRef(count);
countRef.current = count; <span class="cm">// update ref every render</span>
<span class="cm">// use countRef.current in callbacks</span></code></pre>

  <div class="iq-box">
    <div class="iq-header">
      <span class="iq-label">Interview Question</span>
      <span class="iq-level lvl-faang">FAANG Level</span>
    </div>
    <div class="iq-q">Explain tearing in React concurrent mode. How does React 18 prevent it?</div>
    <div class="iq-a">
      <strong>Tearing</strong> occurs when multiple components read the same external store, but React renders them at different times during a concurrent render. Component A reads value=1, React pauses, the store updates to 2, Component B reads value=2 — UI is inconsistent (torn).
      <br><br>
      <strong>React 18 solution:</strong> <code>useSyncExternalStore</code>. It subscribes to external stores with a snapshot mechanism. React detects if the snapshot changed mid-render and re-renders synchronously. Redux, Zustand, and Jotai all updated to use this in their React 18 adapters.
      <br><br>
      <strong>RN implication:</strong> If you're reading from native module state directly (vs through the React reconciler), you can get tearing. Always gate external state reads through <code>useSyncExternalStore</code> or use a proper state management library.
    </div>
  </div>

</section>

<!-- ===== SECTION 4: JS ENGINE ===== -->
<section class="section" id="js-engine">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-num">04</div>
    <div class="section-title-wrap">
      <div class="section-tag">Runtime Internals</div>
      <h1 class="section-title">JavaScript Engine Internals</h1>
      <p class="section-desc">V8, Hermes, JSC internals. Event loop, GC, hidden classes, JIT, and how these directly impact RN performance.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="tags">
    <span class="badge badge-js">JavaScript</span>
    <span class="tag">Hermes</span>
    <span class="tag">V8</span>
    <span class="tag">JSC</span>
    <span class="tag">Event Loop</span>
    <span class="tag">GC</span>
    <span class="tag">JIT</span>
  </div>

  <h2>V8 vs Hermes vs JavaScriptCore</h2>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Engine</th><th>Platform</th><th>JIT</th><th>Startup</th><th>Peak Perf</th><th>GC Strategy</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>V8</td><td>Chrome, Node.js</td><td>TurboFan (full)</td><td>Slower (JIT compile)</td><td>Highest</td><td>Orinoco (generational)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Hermes</td><td>React Native</td><td>None (bytecode AOT)</td><td>Fastest</td><td>Lower peak</td><td>Hades (concurrent)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>JSC</td><td>iOS Safari, old RN</td><td>DFG + FTL</td><td>Medium</td><td>High</td><td>Mark-and-sweep</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>Hermes — Why It Wins for Mobile</h3>
  <p>Hermes compiles JavaScript to bytecode <em>at build time</em> (not at runtime). When the app starts, it reads the pre-compiled bytecode directly — no parsing, no JIT warmup. This is the single biggest TTI improvement for RN apps.</p>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
HERMES EXECUTION MODEL

  Build Time:
  ─────────────────────────────────────────
  JS source → [Hermes compiler] → .hbc bytecode
  (Metro bundles this into your APK/IPA)

  App Runtime:
  ─────────────────────────────────────────
  Load .hbc from disk
        │
        ▼
  Hermes interpreter     ← no parse, no JIT warmup
  (register-based VM)    ← optimized for low RAM
        │
        ▼
  Execute bytecode
  (lazy function compilation: only compile called fns)

  vs V8 runtime:
  Parse JS → AST → Bytecode → [Ignition] → [TurboFan JIT]
  Much slower startup, but peak throughput higher

  HADES GC (concurrent):
  - Concurrent Mark: runs on background thread while JS executes
  - Young Gen: 256KB, collected every few seconds
  - Old Gen: Incremental evacuation, minimal pause time
  - Result: ~3ms max GC pauses vs ~50ms in old GC
</pre>
  </div>

  <h2>The Event Loop — Complete Mental Model</h2>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
JAVASCRIPT EVENT LOOP

  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │              CALL STACK                      │
  │  main() → fn1() → fn2() → ...               │
  │  (LIFO, synchronous)                         │
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                    │ when empty ↓
  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │           MICROTASK QUEUE                    │
  │  Promise.then, queueMicrotask, async/await   │
  │  ← DRAINED COMPLETELY before next macrotask  │
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                    │ when empty ↓
  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │           MACROTASK QUEUE                    │
  │  setTimeout, setInterval, I/O callbacks,     │
  │  MessageChannel, requestAnimationFrame*      │
  │  ← ONE task dequeued per loop iteration      │
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────┘

EXECUTION ORDER (critical for interviews):
  1. Current synchronous code
  2. ALL microtasks (Promise.then chains, queueMicrotask)
  3. ONE macrotask (setTimeout callback)
  4. ALL microtasks generated by step 3
  5. Repeat

EXAMPLE:
  console.log('1');                    // sync → "1"
  setTimeout(() => console.log('2'), 0); // macrotask
  Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log('3')); // microtask
  console.log('4');                    // sync → "4"
  // Output: 1, 4, 3, 2
</pre>
  </div>

  <h3>In React Native — Event Loop Impact</h3>
  <pre data-lang="JavaScript"><code><span class="cm">// Common RN bug: microtask starvation</span>
<span class="kw">async function</span> <span class="fn">processLargeList</span>(items) {
  <span class="cm">// BAD: This chains thousands of microtasks</span>
  <span class="cm">// Starves other operations (touch events, rendering)</span>
  <span class="kw">for</span> (<span class="kw">const</span> item <span class="kw">of</span> items) {
    <span class="kw">await</span> processItem(item); <span class="cm">// microtask per iteration</span>
  }
}

<span class="cm">// BETTER: Yield to event loop periodically</span>
<span class="kw">async function</span> <span class="fn">processLargeListBetter</span>(items) {
  <span class="kw">for</span> (<span class="kw">let</span> i = <span class="num">0</span>; i &lt; items.length; i++) {
    processItem(items[i]);
    <span class="kw">if</span> (i % <span class="num">50</span> === <span class="num">0</span>) {
      <span class="cm">// Yield: allow a macrotask to run (render, touch)</span>
      <span class="kw">await new</span> Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, <span class="num">0</span>));
    }
  }
}

<span class="cm">// BEST: Use InteractionManager for post-animation work</span>
<span class="kw">import</span> { InteractionManager } <span class="kw">from</span> <span class="str">'react-native'</span>;

InteractionManager.runAfterInteractions(() => {
  <span class="cm">// Runs after all animations/interactions complete</span>
  loadHeavyData();
});</code></pre>

  <h2>Hidden Classes & Deoptimization</h2>

  <p>V8 (and Hermes to a lesser extent) optimizes objects with <em>hidden classes</em> — internal types that track object shape. When an object's shape changes unexpectedly, V8 deoptimizes ("bails out") from JIT-compiled code to interpreted execution.</p>

  <pre data-lang="JavaScript"><code><span class="cm">// BAD: Shape changes — different hidden classes</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> obj1 = {};
obj1.x = <span class="num">1</span>;  <span class="cm">// HiddenClass A → B</span>
obj1.y = <span class="num">2</span>;  <span class="cm">// HiddenClass B → C</span>

<span class="cm">// GOOD: Same shape — same hidden class, monomorphic</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> obj2 = { x: <span class="num">1</span>, y: <span class="num">2</span> }; <span class="cm">// HiddenClass X (stable)</span>

<span class="cm">// RN Impact: Component props objects</span>
<span class="cm">// Inline style objects created each render → new shape each time</span>
<span class="cm">// → megamorphic IC → slower style processing</span>

<span class="cm">// BAD (new object every render)</span>
&lt;View style={{ flex: <span class="num">1</span>, backgroundColor: color }} /&gt;

<span class="cm">// GOOD (stable reference, same hidden class)</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> styles = StyleSheet.create({ container: { flex: <span class="num">1</span> } });
<span class="cm">// Combined dynamic+static:</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> dynamicStyle = useMemo(() => ({ backgroundColor: color }), [color]);
&lt;View style={[styles.container, dynamicStyle]} /&gt;</code></pre>

  <h2>Memory Leaks in React Native</h2>

  <pre data-lang="JavaScript"><code><span class="cm">// LEAK 1: Event listener not removed</span>
useEffect(() => {
  <span class="kw">const</span> sub = DeviceEventEmitter.addListener(<span class="str">'event'</span>, handler);
  <span class="cm">// Missing: return () => sub.remove();</span>
}, []);

<span class="cm">// LEAK 2: setState on unmounted component</span>
useEffect(() => {
  <span class="kw">let</span> mounted = <span class="num">true</span>;
  fetch(<span class="str">'/data'</span>).then(data => {
    <span class="kw">if</span> (mounted) setState(data); <span class="cm">// check before setState</span>
  });
  <span class="kw">return</span> () => { mounted = <span class="num">false</span>; };
}, []);

<span class="cm">// LEAK 3: Global store references to component callbacks</span>
<span class="cm">// EventBus, global subscriptions holding component refs</span>
<span class="cm">// Always cleanup in useEffect return</span>

<span class="cm">// LEAK 4: Circular references in closures</span>
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">createLeak</span>() {
  <span class="kw">const</span> data = <span class="kw">new</span> Array(<span class="num">1000000</span>).fill(<span class="num">0</span>);
  <span class="kw">return</span> {
    getSize: () => data.length, <span class="cm">// holds ref to data</span>
    <span class="cm">// Even when you discard this object, closure keeps data alive</span>
  };
}</code></pre>

  <div class="iq-box">
    <div class="iq-header">
      <span class="iq-label">Interview Question</span>
      <span class="iq-level lvl-senior">Senior Level</span>
    </div>
    <div class="iq-q">What is the difference between microtasks and macrotasks, and how does async/await relate to them?</div>
    <div class="iq-a">
      <strong>Microtasks</strong> run immediately after the current task completes, before the event loop picks up the next macrotask. Every Promise resolution enqueues a microtask. The microtask queue is fully drained between macrotasks.
      <br><br>
      <strong>async/await is syntactic sugar over Promises</strong>. Every <code>await</code> suspends the async function and schedules its continuation as a microtask when the awaited value resolves. So:
      <pre><code>async function foo() {
  console.log('A');
  await Promise.resolve();  // schedules continuation as microtask
  console.log('B');
}
foo(); console.log('C');
// Output: A, C, B</code></pre>
      <strong>In React Native:</strong> Heavy async chains (100s of awaits) can starve the render loop. Use <code>InteractionManager</code> or chunk work into macrotasks for UI-critical paths.
    </div>
  </div>

</section>

<!-- ===== SECTION 5: DISTRIBUTED SYSTEMS ===== -->
<section class="section" id="distributed">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-num">05</div>
    <div class="section-title-wrap">
      <div class="section-tag">Backend Architecture for Mobile</div>
      <h1 class="section-title">Distributed Systems for Mobile Engineers</h1>
      <p class="section-desc">What every mobile Staff engineer must understand about the systems their app talks to — from CDN to Kafka to CAP theorem.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>The Mobile ↔ Backend Contract</h2>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
TYPICAL PRODUCTION MOBILE ARCHITECTURE

  React Native App
       │
       │ HTTPS/HTTP2 / WebSocket / gRPC-Web
       ▼
  API Gateway (Kong, AWS API GW, Nginx)
  ├── Rate limiting (token bucket, per user)
  ├── Auth (JWT validation, OAuth2)
  ├── Request routing
  └── SSL termination
       │
       ├──────────────────────────────┐
       ▼                              ▼
  REST/GraphQL API              WebSocket Server
  (Node/Go/Python)              (Socket.io/uWS)
       │                              │
       ▼                              ▼
  Redis Cache        ←────────  Message Broker
  (read-through)                (Kafka/RabbitMQ)
       │
       ▼
  Primary DB          Read Replicas
  (Postgres/MySQL)  ←────────────
       │
       ▼
  Object Storage (S3/GCS)    CDN (CloudFront)
  (images, videos)      ←────── (edge cache)
</pre>
  </div>

  <h2>CDN — How Mobile Apps Use It</h2>
  <p>A CDN (Content Delivery Network) caches static assets at edge nodes geographically close to users. For mobile apps: images, fonts, JS bundles (OTA updates), and video segments all go through CDN.</p>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <span class="callout-icon">💡</span>
    <div class="callout-content">
      <div class="callout-title">Mobile-Specific CDN Considerations</div>
      Cache-Control headers determine how long the mobile HTTP cache (NSURLCache on iOS, OkHttp cache on Android) stores responses. <code>max-age=31536000, immutable</code> on versioned assets (hashed filenames) prevents unnecessary redownloads. OTA bundle URLs should be immutable with version in the URL path.
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Authentication Flows</h2>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
OAUTH2 + JWT MOBILE FLOW

  App                     Auth Server              Resource Server
  ─────                   ────────────             ───────────────
  Redirect to /authorize ──►
  (client_id, scope,
   code_challenge [PKCE])
                           User authenticates
                           ◄── authorization_code
  POST /token
  (code, code_verifier) ──►
                           Verify PKCE
                           ◄── { access_token (JWT, 15min)
                                  refresh_token (opaque, 30d)
                                  id_token (OIDC) }

  API call + Bearer JWT ───────────────────────────►
                                                   Validate JWT signature
                                                   (no DB lookup needed!)
                                                   ◄── 200 response

  JWT expires (401) → POST /token {refresh_token} ─►
                           ◄── new access_token

SECURITY IN RN:
  - Store tokens in Keychain (iOS) / EncryptedSharedPreferences (Android)
  - NEVER AsyncStorage for tokens (unencrypted)
  - PKCE prevents auth code interception
  - Token binding to device fingerprint (advanced)
</pre>
  </div>

  <h2>WebSocket Scaling</h2>
  <pre data-lang="JavaScript"><code><span class="cm">// Production WebSocket with reconnection strategy</span>
<span class="kw">class</span> <span class="type">WebSocketManager</span> {
  <span class="kw">private</span> ws: WebSocket | null = null;
  <span class="kw">private</span> reconnectDelay = <span class="num">1000</span>;
  <span class="kw">private</span> maxDelay = <span class="num">30000</span>;
  <span class="kw">private</span> pingInterval: ReturnType&lt;<span class="kw">typeof</span> setInterval&gt;;

  connect() {
    <span class="kw">this</span>.ws = <span class="kw">new</span> WebSocket(WS_URL);

    <span class="kw">this</span>.ws.onopen = () => {
      <span class="kw">this</span>.reconnectDelay = <span class="num">1000</span>; <span class="cm">// reset backoff</span>
      <span class="kw">this</span>.startHeartbeat();
    };

    <span class="kw">this</span>.ws.onclose = () => {
      <span class="kw">this</span>.stopHeartbeat();
      <span class="cm">// Exponential backoff with jitter</span>
      <span class="kw">const</span> jitter = Math.random() * <span class="num">1000</span>;
      setTimeout(() => <span class="kw">this</span>.connect(),
        Math.min(<span class="kw">this</span>.reconnectDelay + jitter, <span class="kw">this</span>.maxDelay));
      <span class="kw">this</span>.reconnectDelay = Math.min(<span class="kw">this</span>.reconnectDelay * <span class="num">2</span>, <span class="kw">this</span>.maxDelay);
    };
  }

  <span class="kw">private</span> startHeartbeat() {
    <span class="kw">this</span>.pingInterval = setInterval(() => {
      <span class="kw">if</span> (<span class="kw">this</span>.ws?.readyState === WebSocket.OPEN) {
        <span class="kw">this</span>.ws.send(JSON.stringify({ type: <span class="str">'ping'</span> }));
      }
    }, <span class="num">25000</span>); <span class="cm">// below NAT timeout (~30s)</span>
  }
}</code></pre>

  <h2>CAP Theorem for Mobile</h2>

  <div class="card-grid">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">C — Consistency</div>
      <div class="card-body">Every read receives the most recent write. Mobile impact: offline writes might be stale when the user goes online. Healthcare apps require strong consistency (patient records).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">A — Availability</div>
      <div class="card-body">Every request receives a response (might be stale). Mobile impact: optimistic updates show cached data while real data syncs. Social feeds prefer availability over consistency.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">P — Partition Tolerance</div>
      <div class="card-body">System works despite network partitions. Always required for mobile (users lose connectivity). You choose: CP (banking) or AP (social, e-commerce) for mobile scenarios.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>GraphQL for Mobile — Tradeoffs</h2>

  <div class="diff-grid">
    <div class="diff-col good">
      <div class="diff-label">✓ GraphQL Advantages for Mobile</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Fetch exactly needed fields → smaller payloads</li>
        <li>Single round-trip for complex queries</li>
        <li>Strong typing with codegen → type-safe hooks</li>
        <li>Subscriptions via WebSocket for real-time</li>
        <li>Relay/Apollo client-side caching</li>
        <li>Schema-first development (mocking, docs)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="diff-col bad">
      <div class="diff-label">↓ GraphQL Challenges</div>
      <ul>
        <li>N+1 query problem on the server</li>
        <li>Complex caching (vs REST + HTTP cache headers)</li>
        <li>Larger initial payload (introspection)</li>
        <li>Query complexity → needs depth limiting</li>
        <li>Less suited for file uploads (multipart workarounds)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Observability: What Mobile Engineers Control</h2>

  <pre data-lang="JavaScript"><code><span class="cm">// Distributed tracing from mobile</span>
<span class="kw">import</span> * <span class="kw">as</span> Sentry <span class="kw">from</span> <span class="str">'@sentry/react-native'</span>;

<span class="cm">// Every API call creates a span tied to the trace</span>
<span class="kw">async function</span> <span class="fn">fetchUserProfile</span>(userId: string) {
  <span class="kw">const</span> transaction = Sentry.startTransaction({
    name: <span class="str">'fetchUserProfile'</span>,
    op: <span class="str">'http.client'</span>
  });

  <span class="kw">try</span> {
    <span class="kw">const</span> span = transaction.startChild({
      op: <span class="str">'db.query'</span>,
      description: <span class="str">'GET /users/:id'</span>
    });

    <span class="kw">const</span> result = <span class="kw">await</span> api.get(<span class="str">`/users/${userId}`</span>, {
      headers: {
        <span class="cm">// Pass trace context to backend for correlation</span>
        <span class="str">'sentry-trace'</span>: span.toTraceparent(),
        <span class="str">'baggage'</span>: Sentry.getCurrentHub().getScope()
          ?.getPropagationContext().traceId
      }
    });

    span.finish();
    <span class="kw">return</span> result;
  } <span class="kw">finally</span> {
    transaction.finish();
  }
}</code></pre>

  <div class="iq-box">
    <div class="iq-header">
      <span class="iq-label">Interview Question</span>
      <span class="iq-level lvl-staff">Staff Level</span>
    </div>
    <div class="iq-q">Your mobile app has a chat feature. The backend team asks whether to use REST polling, WebSocket, or Server-Sent Events. What do you recommend and why?</div>
    <div class="iq-a">
      <strong>Recommendation: WebSocket with SSE fallback.</strong>
      <br><br>
      <strong>REST polling:</strong> Inefficient — constant requests even when no messages. Battery drain. Works as last resort.
      <br><br>
      <strong>SSE (Server-Sent Events):</strong> Server → client only. Good for feeds/notifications but can't send messages back on the same connection. HTTP/1.1 has 6-connection limit (SSE uses one). iOS NSURLSession handles SSE natively but RN needs polyfill.
      <br><br>
      <strong>WebSocket:</strong> Full-duplex. Perfect for chat. Challenges: NAT timeouts (heartbeat every 25s), reconnection (exponential backoff), scaling (sticky sessions or pub/sub layer like Redis Pub/Sub). Use socket.io for automatic fallback and reconnection.
      <br><br>
      <strong>Mobile-specific concerns:</strong> Background mode — both platforms limit background socket connections. iOS: background task + push to wake. Android: FCM for wakeup, foreground service for active chat. I'd use a dedicated WebSocket connection with offline queue (SQLite) + push notifications for when app is backgrounded.
    </div>
  </div>

</section>

<!-- ===== SECTION 6: TESTING ===== -->
<section class="section" id="testing">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-num">06</div>
    <div class="section-title-wrap">
      <div class="section-tag">Quality Engineering</div>
      <h1 class="section-title">Full Testing Strategy</h1>
      <p class="section-desc">Jest, RNTL, Detox, Maestro — complete production testing pipeline, CI integration, flaky test debugging, and release confidence.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>The Testing Pyramid for React Native</h2>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
                    ╔══════════════╗
                    ║   E2E Tests  ║  ← Detox / Maestro
                    ║  (few, slow) ║    ~5–15 key flows
                    ╚══════╤═══════╝
              ╔════════════╧════════════╗
              ║   Integration Tests      ║  ← RNTL + MSW
              ║  (screens, user flows)   ║    ~50–200 tests
              ╚════════════╤═════════════╝
      ╔════════════════════╧═════════════════════╗
      ║            Unit Tests                     ║  ← Jest
      ║  (utils, hooks, business logic, reducers) ║    ~500+ tests
      ╚══════════════════════════════════════════╝

PRINCIPLE: High confidence, low cost.
- Units: fast feedback (< 5s for full suite)
- Integration: catch screen-level regressions
- E2E: protect critical revenue paths (login, checkout, core flow)
</pre>
  </div>

  <h2>Jest — Production Configuration</h2>

  <pre data-lang="JavaScript"><code>// jest.config.js — production setup
module.exports = {
  preset: 'react-native',
  setupFilesAfterFramework: [
    '@testing-library/jest-native/extend-expect',
    './jest.setup.ts',
  ],
  moduleNameMapper: {
    // Alias resolution (same as tsconfig paths)
    '^@/(.*)$': '<rootDir>/src/$1',
    // Mock static assets
    '\\.(png|jpg|svg)$': '<rootDir>/__mocks__/fileMock.js',
  },
  transformIgnorePatterns: [
    // Transform RN packages (they ship untranspiled ESM)
    'node_modules/(?!(react-native|@react-native|react-native-reanimated|' +
    '@react-navigation|react-native-screens|react-native-safe-area-context' +
    ')/)',
  ],
  collectCoverageFrom: [
    'src/**/*.{ts,tsx}',
    '!src/**/*.stories.tsx',
    '!src/**/*.d.ts',
  ],
  coverageThresholds: {
    global: { branches: 70, functions: 80, lines: 80 },
  },
  testTimeout: 15000,
};</code></pre>

  <h2>React Native Testing Library (RNTL)</h2>

  <pre data-lang="TypeScript"><code>// Integration test: full screen with mocked API
import { render, screen, fireEvent, waitFor } from '@testing-library/react-native';
import { server } from '../mocks/server'; // MSW server
import { http, HttpResponse } from 'msw';
import { LoginScreen } from '../screens/LoginScreen';
import { AppProviders } from '../AppProviders';

const renderWithProviders = (ui: React.ReactElement) =>
  render(ui, { wrapper: AppProviders });

describe('LoginScreen', () => {
  it('shows validation errors for empty fields', async () => {
    renderWithProviders(<LoginScreen />);
    fireEvent.press(screen.getByText('Login'));
    expect(await screen.findByText('Email is required')).toBeVisible();
  });

  it('navigates to Home on successful login', async () => {
    // Override MSW handler for this test
    server.use(
      http.post('/auth/login', () =>
        HttpResponse.json({ token: 'fake-jwt', user: { id: '1' } })
      )
    );

    renderWithProviders(<LoginScreen />);
    fireEvent.changeText(screen.getByPlaceholderText('Email'), 'user@test.com');
    fireEvent.changeText(screen.getByPlaceholderText('Password'), 'password123');
    fireEvent.press(screen.getByText('Login'));

    await waitFor(() => {
      expect(screen.getByTestId('home-screen')).toBeVisible();
    });
  });
});

// Testing a custom hook
import { renderHook, act } from '@testing-library/react-native';
import { useCart } from '../hooks/useCart';

test('adding item increases cart count', () => {
  const { result } = renderHook(() => useCart(), { wrapper: AppProviders });
  act(() => {
    result.current.addItem({ id: '1', price: 10, name: 'Widget' });
  });
  expect(result.current.count).toBe(1);
  expect(result.current.total).toBe(10);
});</code></pre>

  <h2>Mocking Native Modules</h2>

  <pre data-lang="TypeScript"><code>// __mocks__/@react-native-community/netinfo.ts
// Full mock for CI (no native runtime)
const mockNetInfo = {
  fetch: jest.fn().mockResolvedValue({
    isConnected: true,
    isInternetReachable: true,
    type: 'wifi',
  }),
  addEventListener: jest.fn(() => jest.fn()), // returns unsubscribe
  useNetInfo: jest.fn().mockReturnValue({ isConnected: true }),
};
export default mockNetInfo;

// jest.setup.ts — global mocks
jest.mock('react-native-reanimated', () => {
  const Reanimated = require('react-native-reanimated/mock');
  Reanimated.default.call = () => {}; // silence warnings
  return Reanimated;
});

jest.mock('@react-native-async-storage/async-storage', () =>
  require('@react-native-async-storage/async-storage/jest/async-storage-mock')
);

// TurboModule mock
jest.mock('../src/native/NativeCrypto', () => ({
  hash: jest.fn().mockResolvedValue('mocked-hash'),
}));</code></pre>

  <h2>Detox — E2E Framework</h2>

  <pre data-lang="TypeScript"><code>// e2e/login.test.ts
import { device, element, by, expect as detoxExpect, waitFor } from 'detox';

describe('Login Flow', () => {
  beforeAll(async () => {
    await device.launchApp({ newInstance: true });
  });

  beforeEach(async () => {
    await device.reloadReactNative(); // fresh JS state
  });

  it('completes full login → home flow', async () => {
    // Wait for splash to finish
    await waitFor(element(by.id('login-screen')))
      .toBeVisible()
      .withTimeout(5000);

    await element(by.id('email-input')).typeText('user@test.com');
    await element(by.id('password-input')).typeText('password123');

    // Dismiss keyboard before tap
    await element(by.id('password-input')).tapReturnKey();

    await element(by.id('login-button')).tap();

    // Assert navigation happened
    await waitFor(element(by.id('home-screen')))
      .toBeVisible()
      .withTimeout(8000);

    // Assert user name displayed
    await detoxExpect(element(by.text('Welcome, User'))).toBeVisible();
  });

  it('handles biometric auth', async () => {
    await element(by.id('biometric-button')).tap();
    // Simulate biometric on simulator
    await device.matchFace(); // iOS; matchFinger() for Android
    await waitFor(element(by.id('home-screen'))).toBeVisible().withTimeout(3000);
  });
});</code></pre>

  <h3>Maestro — The Simpler E2E Alternative</h3>
  <pre data-lang="YAML"><code># flows/login.yaml
appId: com.myapp
---
- launchApp:
    clearState: true
- assertVisible: "Login"
- tapOn:
    id: "email-input"
- inputText: "user@test.com"
- tapOn:
    id: "password-input"
- inputText: "password123"
- tapOn: "Login"
- assertVisible:
    id: "home-screen"
    timeout: 8000
- assertVisible: "Welcome"
# Run: maestro test flows/login.yaml
# CI: maestro cloud --apiKey $MAESTRO_KEY flows/</code></pre>

  <div class="callout callout-warn">
    <span class="callout-icon">⚡</span>
    <div class="callout-content">
      <div class="callout-title">Flaky E2E Test Debugging Strategy</div>
      <strong>1. Identify:</strong> Track flake rate per test in CI (re-run failed tests 3x, flag any that pass on retry). <strong>2. Categorize:</strong> Animation timing (add waitFor + timeout), async data (mock APIs in E2E or use seedable test data), device resource (memory pressure kills app mid-test → use simulator with 4GB+). <strong>3. Fix:</strong> Replace hardcoded sleeps with waitFor. Use test IDs not text (text changes with i18n). Isolate tests (clearState: true). Add retry strategy in CI only for known infrastructure flakes.
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>CI Testing Pipeline</h2>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
CI PIPELINE (GitHub Actions / Bitrise)

PR Opened
    │
    ├─ Lint + TypeScript check     (~30s)
    ├─ Unit tests (Jest)           (~2min)
    ├─ Integration tests (RNTL)    (~3min)
    │
    ├─ [On merge to main]
    │   ├─ E2E Android (Detox on emulator)  (~15min)
    │   ├─ E2E iOS (Detox on simulator)     (~15min)
    │   └─ (Parallel)
    │
    ├─ [Nightly]
    │   ├─ Full E2E suite (real devices - Firebase Test Lab)
    │   ├─ Performance benchmarks
    │   └─ Visual regression (Percy/Chromatic for Storybook)
    │
    └─ Release
        ├─ Build Android AAB (release)
        ├─ Build iOS IPA (release)
        ├─ Upload to Firebase App Distribution
        └─ Notify QA channel
</pre>
  </div>

  <div class="iq-box">
    <div class="iq-header">
      <span class="iq-label">Interview Question</span>
      <span class="iq-level lvl-staff">Staff Level</span>
    </div>
    <div class="iq-q">How do you test a TurboModule that does BLE scanning? What's your strategy at each layer?</div>
    <div class="iq-a">
      <strong>Unit (Jest):</strong> Mock the TurboModule entirely — <code>jest.mock('../native/NativeBLE', () => ({ startScan: jest.fn() }))</code>. Test the JS-layer logic (event handling, state transitions) in isolation.
      <br><br>
      <strong>Integration (RNTL):</strong> Mock the BLE module, emit fake device events via <code>DeviceEventEmitter.emit('BLEDevice', { id: 'XX:XX', rssi: -45 })</code>. Test that the screen renders device list correctly.
      <br><br>
      <strong>Native unit (Android/iOS):</strong> JUnit/XCTest on the TurboModule itself, mocking the platform BLE API. Verify the correct JS events are emitted.
      <br><br>
      <strong>E2E:</strong> Only on real physical devices with BLE hardware. Use a known test BLE peripheral (or a second device running BLE advertiser). Maestro or Detox with a custom helper that controls the peripheral. This runs in nightly CI only, not on every PR — too slow and hardware-dependent.
    </div>
  </div>

</section>

<!-- ===== SECTION 7: ARCHITECTURE ===== -->
<section class="section" id="architecture">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-num">07</div>
    <div class="section-title-wrap">
      <div class="section-tag">Software Design</div>
      <h1 class="section-title">Software Architecture Patterns</h1>
      <p class="section-desc">Clean Architecture, MVVM, MVI, feature-based monorepo design, DI, SOLID, and real-world scalable RN folder structures.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Clean Architecture for React Native</h2>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
CLEAN ARCHITECTURE LAYERS (Onion Model)

┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                   PRESENTATION                       │
│   Screens, Components, ViewModels, Navigation        │
│   (React, Reanimated, RNTL)                          │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                   APPLICATION                        │
│   Use Cases / Interactors                            │
│   (orchestrate domain + infra, no framework deps)    │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                     DOMAIN                           │
│   Entities, Value Objects, Domain Events             │
│   Repository Interfaces (no implementation!)         │
│   (pure TypeScript, zero dependencies)               │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                 INFRASTRUCTURE                       │
│   API clients, SQLite, MMKV, BLE, Camera             │
│   Repository Implementations                         │
│   (implements Domain interfaces)                     │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

DEPENDENCY RULE: Dependencies point INWARD only.
Domain knows nothing about API or React.
</pre>
  </div>

  <h2>Scalable Folder Structure</h2>

  <pre data-lang="bash"><code>src/
├── app/                      # App-level config
│   ├── navigation/           # React Navigation stacks
│   ├── providers/            # Context providers, DI container
│   └── store/                # Global state (Zustand/Redux)
│
├── features/                 # Feature-based modules
│   ├── auth/
│   │   ├── components/       # AuthForm, BiometricButton
│   │   ├── hooks/            # useAuth, useSession
│   │   ├── screens/          # LoginScreen, RegisterScreen
│   │   ├── services/         # AuthService (use case)
│   │   ├── store/            # authSlice or authStore
│   │   └── types/            # AuthUser, LoginPayload
│   │
│   ├── feed/
│   │   ├── api/              # feedApi (RTK Query / React Query)
│   │   ├── components/       # FeedCard, FeedList
│   │   ├── hooks/            # useFeed, useInfiniteScroll
│   │   └── screens/          # FeedScreen
│   │
│   └── [feature]/
│
├── shared/                   # Cross-feature shared code
│   ├── components/           # Button, Input, Modal (design system)
│   ├── hooks/                # useDebounce, useKeyboard, useNetwork
│   ├── utils/                # formatDate, validators, crypto
│   ├── constants/            # apiEndpoints, colors, spacing
│   └── types/                # ApiResponse, Pagination, etc.
│
├── infrastructure/           # Data layer implementations
│   ├── api/                  # axios instance, interceptors, base client
│   ├── storage/              # MMKV, AsyncStorage wrappers
│   ├── analytics/            # Segment, Amplitude adapters
│   └── native/               # TurboModule JS wrappers
│
└── domain/                   # Pure business logic
    ├── entities/             # User, Order, Product
    ├── repositories/         # IUserRepository (interface)
    └── usecases/             # LoginUseCase, PlaceOrderUseCase</code></pre>

  <h2>MVI (Model-View-Intent) for Complex Screens</h2>

  <pre data-lang="TypeScript"><code>// MVI pattern: unidirectional data flow, testable state machine
// Ideal for complex screens: cart, checkout, multi-step forms

type CartState =
  | { status: 'idle' }
  | { status: 'loading' }
  | { status: 'loaded'; items: CartItem[]; total: number }
  | { status: 'error'; message: string };

type CartIntent =
  | { type: 'ADD_ITEM'; item: CartItem }
  | { type: 'REMOVE_ITEM'; id: string }
  | { type: 'CHECKOUT' }
  | { type: 'CLEAR' };

function cartReducer(state: CartState, intent: CartIntent): CartState {
  switch (intent.type) {
    case 'ADD_ITEM':
      if (state.status !== 'loaded') return state;
      const newItems = [...state.items, intent.item];
      return {
        ...state,
        items: newItems,
        total: newItems.reduce((s, i) => s + i.price * i.qty, 0),
      };
    case 'REMOVE_ITEM':
      if (state.status !== 'loaded') return state;
      return {
        ...state,
        items: state.items.filter(i => i.id !== intent.id),
      };
    default:
      return state;
  }
}

// In component
function CartScreen() {
  const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(cartReducer, { status: 'idle' });

  // Pure render from state — highly testable
  return (
    <CartView
      state={state}
      onAddItem={(item) => dispatch({ type: 'ADD_ITEM', item })}
      onCheckout={() => dispatch({ type: 'CHECKOUT' })}
    />
  );
}</code></pre>

  <h2>Dependency Injection in React Native</h2>

  <pre data-lang="TypeScript"><code>// DI Container (using tsyringe or manual DI)
// Allows swapping implementations (prod vs test vs staging)

// Domain interface
interface IAnalyticsService {
  track(event: string, props?: Record<string, unknown>): void;
}

// Implementations
class SegmentAnalytics implements IAnalyticsService {
  track(event: string, props = {}) {
    analytics.track(event, props); // Segment SDK
  }
}

class NoopAnalytics implements IAnalyticsService {
  track() {} // silent in tests/dev
}

// Container setup
const container = {
  analytics: __DEV__
    ? new NoopAnalytics()
    : new SegmentAnalytics(),
  authRepo: new ApiAuthRepository(httpClient),
  userRepo: new ApiUserRepository(httpClient),
} as const;

// React Context DI
const DIContext = React.createContext(container);
export const useContainer = () => React.useContext(DIContext);

// In test: override specific services
const testContainer = {
  ...container,
  analytics: new NoopAnalytics(),
  authRepo: new MockAuthRepository(),
};</code></pre>

  <h2>Monorepo Architecture with Turborepo</h2>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
MONOREPO STRUCTURE (RN + Web + Backend)

apps/
├── mobile/          ← React Native app
├── web/             ← Next.js / Expo Web
└── admin/           ← CRA / Vite admin panel

packages/
├── ui/              ← Shared design system (RN + Web via platform files)
│   ├── Button.tsx
│   ├── Button.native.tsx   ← RN-specific
│   └── Button.web.tsx      ← Web-specific
│
├── api-client/      ← Generated from OpenAPI spec (shared types)
├── domain/          ← Business logic, entities (pure TS)
├── utils/           ← Date formatters, validators
└── config/          ← ESLint, TypeScript, Jest configs

TURBOREPO CACHING:
- Caches build outputs between CI runs
- Only rebuilds affected packages
- Parallel task execution
- ~70% CI time reduction for monorepos

turbo.json:
{
  "pipeline": {
    "build": {
      "dependsOn": ["^build"],
      "outputs": ["dist/**", ".next/**"]
    },
    "test": { "dependsOn": ["build"] },
    "lint": {}
  }
}
</pre>
  </div>

  <div class="iq-box">
    <div class="iq-header">
      <span class="iq-label">Interview Question</span>
      <span class="iq-level lvl-staff">Staff Level</span>
    </div>
    <div class="iq-q">You're building a white-label app platform for 10 enterprise clients, each with custom branding, features, and API endpoints. How do you architect this?</div>
    <div class="iq-a">
      <strong>Three layers of customization:</strong>
      <br><br>
      <strong>1. Build-time (Flavors/Schemes):</strong> Android product flavors + iOS schemes per client. Each has its own <code>google-services.json</code>, bundle ID, signing cert, app icon, splash. Environment config injected via build config fields. CI builds all flavors in parallel.
      <br><br>
      <strong>2. Runtime (Theme/Config injection):</strong> Remote config (Firebase Remote Config / own CMS) drives colors, typography, feature flags, API base URL. A <code>ThemeProvider</code> at the root reads client config. All components consume from theme, never hardcoded colors.
      <br><br>
      <strong>3. Feature flags (per-tenant):</strong> A feature flag service (LaunchDarkly / custom) gates entire feature modules per client. Dynamic navigation config — screens are registered only if the feature is enabled for that tenant. This avoids dead code in the bundle (use dynamic imports + React.lazy).
      <br><br>
      <strong>Code structure:</strong> Core features in <code>packages/core</code>. Client-specific overrides in <code>apps/client-name</code>. Theming via design tokens JSON per client. Automated: adding a new client = new config JSON + new build flavor + CI lane. No code fork.
    </div>
  </div>

</section>

<!-- ===== SECTION 8: INCIDENTS ===== -->
<section class="section" id="incidents">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-num">08</div>
    <div class="section-title-wrap">
      <div class="section-tag">Production Engineering</div>
      <h1 class="section-title">Production Incidents & Debugging</h1>
      <p class="section-desc">Real crash debugging, memory leak hunts, ANR analysis, OTA rollbacks, and how Staff engineers lead incident response.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Incident Response Framework</h2>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
INCIDENT LIFECYCLE (Staff Engineer Role)

DETECT → TRIAGE → MITIGATE → RESOLVE → POSTMORTEM

DETECT:
  - Crashlytics alert: crash-free rate drops below 99%
  - Sentry alert: new error spike (>50/min)
  - PagerDuty from backend: 5xx rate spike
  - App Store reviews: sudden surge of 1-star

TRIAGE (first 5 min):
  - Scope: which version? which platform? which users?
  - Severity: revenue impact? critical path (auth, payment)?
  - Assign: incident commander, comms owner

MITIGATE (next 15 min):
  - Kill switch: feature flag to disable broken feature
  - OTA rollback: CodePush/EAS Update rollback to last good bundle
  - Force update: server-side min version enforcement
  - Rollback server-side change (if backend-caused)

RESOLVE:
  - Root cause identified
  - Fix deployed
  - Monitoring confirms recovery

POSTMORTEM (24-48h):
  - Timeline reconstruction
  - 5 Whys root cause analysis
  - Action items with owners + deadlines
  - Blameless culture
</pre>
  </div>

  <h2>Crash Debugging Walkthroughs</h2>

  <div class="incident">
    <div class="incident-header">
      <span class="incident-badge">P0 Incident</span>
      <span class="incident-title">Native crash on Android 14 — 4% crash rate on launch</span>
    </div>
    <p><strong>Signal:</strong> Firebase Crashlytics showed <code>SIGSEGV</code> in <code>libhermes.so</code> at <code>0x3f2a</code>. Only Android 14 (API 34), arm64.</p>
    <p><strong>Step 1:</strong> Get symbolicated stack. Download <code>libhermes.so</code> with debug symbols from Hermes GitHub release matching your exact version. Run:</p>
    <pre data-lang="bash"><code>llvm-symbolizer --obj=libhermes.so 0x3f2a
# Output: hermes::vm::JSObject::getNamedSlotValue(...) at Object.cpp:245</code></pre>
    <p><strong>Step 2:</strong> Narrow to JS code. Enable Hermes source maps: in Metro config, set <code>hermesFlagsRelease: ['-O', '-output-source-map']</code>. Upload source map to Sentry/Firebase.</p>
    <p><strong>Step 3:</strong> Found — a native module was calling into JSI after the React host was destroyed (app backgrounded → system killed activity → JSI runtime torn down). Module had no nil-check on runtime pointer.</p>
    <p><strong>Fix:</strong> Added <code>if (!runtime_) return;</code> guard in C++ module. Added JSI invalidation listener. Added CI step that runs address sanitizer on debug builds.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="incident">
    <div class="incident-header">
      <span class="incident-badge">Memory Leak</span>
      <span class="incident-title">iOS app memory growing 50MB/hr during normal use</span>
    </div>
    <p><strong>Detection:</strong> Instruments → Allocations → Memory growth 50MB over 30min session in production. User reports: app killed after ~2 hours.</p>
    <p><strong>Investigation:</strong></p>
    <pre data-lang="bash"><code># Instruments Leaks template → found: RCTImageView not released
# Mark generation: interact with app, mark heap, interact more, compare
# Found: 2,000 RCTImageView instances alive, expected ~20</code></pre>
    <p><strong>Root cause:</strong> <code>FastImage</code> cache wasn't being cleared. Each navigation push created new images, old ones weren't released because a global cache (a plain JS object) held strong references to image URIs mapped to <code>NativeImage</code> objects.</p>
    <p><strong>Fix:</strong> Implemented LRU cache with max size 200. Added <code>FastImage.clearMemoryCache()</code> on app background. Switched to <code>Image.getSizeWithHeaders</code> for prefetching instead of loading invisible <code>Image</code> components.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>OTA Rollback Strategy</h2>

  <pre data-lang="TypeScript"><code>// EAS Update rollback workflow
// eas.json
{
  "cli": { "version": ">= 7.0.0" },
  "update": {
    "channel": "production",
    "rollbackOnError": true  // auto-rollback on update load failure
  }
}

// Staged rollout with automatic rollback
// 1. Deploy to 5% of users
await eas.update.publish({
  channel: 'production',
  rolloutPercentage: 5,
  message: 'v2.1.0 — new checkout flow',
});

// 2. Monitor Sentry for 30min
// 3. If crash rate > 1% → rollback
await eas.update.rollback({ channel: 'production' });

// Server-side kill switch (belt + suspenders)
// Every app launch checks:
const config = await remoteConfig.fetchAndActivate();
if (config.getBoolean('force_js_rollback')) {
  // Force OTA update to last stable bundle
  await Updates.fetchUpdateAsync();
  await Updates.reloadAsync();
}</code></pre>

  <h2>Hermes Crash Debugging</h2>

  <pre data-lang="bash"><code># Step 1: Get the crash address from Crashlytics
# e.g., libhermes.so +0x1a2b3c

# Step 2: Get Hermes build with symbols
# Match EXACTLY: hermes version in your package.json
npm ls hermes-engine  # find version

# Step 3: Symbolicate
llvm-addr2line -e hermes/build/API/hermes/libhermes.so 0x1a2b3c

# Step 4: JavaScript source map (if bytecode crash)
# metro bundle generates index.android.bundle.map
npx hermes-parser index.android.bundle.map 0x4f2  # bytecode offset

# Sentry auto-symbolication:
# Upload both native symbols + JS source maps in CI:
sentry-cli upload-dif ./app/build/intermediates/cmake/release/obj
sentry-cli sourcemaps upload --dist=100 --release=1.0.0 \
  index.android.bundle index.android.bundle.map</code></pre>

  <h2>Production Monitoring Setup</h2>

  <pre data-lang="TypeScript"><code>// Comprehensive monitoring initialization
import * as Sentry from '@sentry/react-native';

Sentry.init({
  dsn: Config.SENTRY_DSN,
  environment: Config.ENV,
  release: `com.myapp@${Config.VERSION}+${Config.BUILD_NUMBER}`,
  tracesSampleRate: 0.2,           // 20% of sessions traced
  profilesSampleRate: 0.1,         // 10% profiled
  attachScreenshot: true,          // screenshot on crash
  attachViewHierarchy: true,       // view tree on crash

  integrations: [
    new Sentry.ReactNativeTracing({
      routingInstrumentation: new Sentry.ReactNavigationInstrumentation(),
      tracingOrigins: ['api.myapp.com'],
    }),
  ],

  beforeSend(event) {
    // Scrub PII before sending
    if (event.user) {
      delete event.user.email;
      delete event.user.ip_address;
    }
    return event;
  },
});

// Custom performance marks
const transaction = Sentry.startTransaction({ name: 'app_startup' });
const ttfb = transaction.startChild({ op: 'bundle_load' });
// ... bundle loaded
ttfb.finish();
// ... first screen rendered
transaction.finish();</code></pre>

