<section class="section" id="ai">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-num">09</div>
    <div class="section-title-wrap">
      <div class="section-tag">Modern Engineering</div>
      <h1 class="section-title">AI-Assisted Engineering</h1>
      <p class="section-desc">Cursor, Claude Code, Copilot, MCPs — responsible use of AI tools in production engineering, agentic workflows, and prompt engineering for engineers.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Senior Engineer's AI Toolkit (2026)</h2>

  <div class="card-grid">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-icon">⚡</div>
      <div class="card-title">Claude Code</div>
      <div class="card-body">Agentic coding: runs terminal commands, edits multiple files, executes tests in a loop. Best for: refactoring across a codebase, writing complete feature implementations, debugging by running code and reading output. Uses extended context — feed it entire feature modules.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-icon">🖱️</div>
      <div class="card-title">Cursor</div>
      <div class="card-body">Editor-integrated AI with codebase indexing. Ctrl+K for inline edits, Ctrl+L for chat with file context. Composer for multi-file edits. Best for: day-to-day coding, refactoring with context, writing tests for existing code. Rules (system prompt per repo) set coding standards.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-icon">🔗</div>
      <div class="card-title">MCPs (Model Context Protocol)</div>
      <div class="card-body">Standardized tool plugins for AI models. Connect Claude/Cursor to: GitHub (PR reviews), Sentry (read errors), Figma (design tokens), your DB (schema queries), internal docs. Staff engineers build custom MCPs for company-specific workflows.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-icon">🤖</div>
      <div class="card-title">Agentic Workflows</div>
      <div class="card-body">AI that plans + executes multi-step tasks autonomously. Examples: "Find all usages of deprecated API X and migrate to Y across the repo." "Write tests for this module, run them, fix failures, repeat." Requires: clear scope, rollback plan, human review gate.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Effective Prompt Engineering for Engineers</h2>

  <div class="diff-grid">
    <div class="diff-col bad">
      <div class="diff-label">↓ Weak Prompts</div>
      <pre><code>"Fix my bug"

"Write a component"

"Make it faster"

"Review my code"</code></pre>
    </div>
    <div class="diff-col good">
      <div class="diff-label">✓ Production-Grade Prompts</div>
      <pre><code>"You are a React Native performance engineer.
This FlatList renders 1000 items and drops to 45fps
on a Pixel 5. Profile the component tree [paste code].
Identify the top 3 bottlenecks and provide specific
fixes using FlashList + memo + useCallback. Include
before/after performance measurements."

"Refactor this AuthService [paste] to follow Clean
Architecture. Domain layer must have zero React/RN
dependencies. Provide: updated folder structure,
interface definitions, and migration guide."</code></pre>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>AI Code Review Workflow</h2>

  <pre data-lang="bash"><code># .cursorrules (repo-level AI instructions)
You are a Senior React Native engineer reviewing code for production quality.
For every code review, check:
1. Memory leaks: event listeners cleaned up? async state updated after unmount?
2. Performance: unnecessary re-renders? missing memoization? heavy computation in render?
3. Type safety: no 'any' types? proper error typing?
4. Error handling: all promises have .catch? async functions wrapped in try/catch?
5. Security: no tokens in logs? sensitive data in AsyncStorage?
6. Testing: is the code testable? suggest test cases.
Flag with severity: [CRITICAL], [MAJOR], [MINOR], [SUGGESTION]

# GitHub Actions AI PR review (using Claude API)
# .github/workflows/ai-review.yml
- name: AI Code Review
  run: |
    git diff origin/main...HEAD > diff.txt
    claude -p "Review this React Native PR diff for bugs, performance issues,
    and security concerns. Be specific about file + line numbers.
    diff: $(cat diff.txt)" >> $GITHUB_STEP_SUMMARY</code></pre>

  <h2>Risks of AI-Generated Code</h2>

  <div class="callout callout-danger">
    <span class="callout-icon">🚨</span>
    <div class="callout-content">
      <div class="callout-title">AI Hallucination Patterns in Mobile Code</div>
      <strong>1. Invented APIs:</strong> AI generates <code>NativeModules.Camera.captureWithOptions()</code> — this API doesn't exist. Always verify against actual docs.
      <br><strong>2. Version drift:</strong> AI trained on older library versions. React Navigation v5 API vs v7, Reanimated v1 vs v3 patterns are completely different.
      <br><strong>3. Platform inconsistencies:</strong> AI may generate iOS-only code without Android equivalents, or use deprecated Android APIs.
      <br><strong>4. Security omissions:</strong> AI-generated auth code often omits PKCE, token rotation, certificate pinning.
      <br><strong>5. Test false confidence:</strong> AI-generated tests that always pass — mocks so aggressive they test nothing.
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Responsible AI Use — Staff Engineer Standards</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Own what you ship:</strong> AI-generated code you commit is code you own. Review every line as if you wrote it.</li>
    <li><strong>Use AI for acceleration, not replacement of thinking:</strong> Architecture decisions, security design, and performance trade-offs require human judgment.</li>
    <li><strong>Establish team AI norms:</strong> Document which AI tools are approved, data sensitivity rules (no customer data in prompts), review requirements for AI-heavy PRs.</li>
    <li><strong>AI for undifferentiated work:</strong> Boilerplate, tests, documentation, migration scripts — high ROI. Business logic, security-critical code — use AI as a collaborator, verify everything.</li>
    <li><strong>Build internal MCPs:</strong> Connect AI to your internal systems (Jira, design system docs, API specs) for context-aware assistance specific to your codebase.</li>
  </ul>

</section>

