  <h2>Writing an RFC (Request for Comments)</h2>

  <pre data-lang="Markdown"><code># RFC-042: Migrate React Native Bridge to New Architecture

## Status: DRAFT | Author: @yourname | Date: 2026-01-15

## Summary
Migrate our RN app from the Old Architecture (bridge) to New Architecture
(JSI + Fabric + TurboModules) to achieve 40% startup improvement and
unlock concurrent React features.

## Motivation
- Current TTI (Time to Interactive): 3.2s on Pixel 5
- Bridge serialization costs: 120ms per complex interaction
- React 18 concurrent features blocked by sync bridge
- 3 production crashes/week from bridge threading issues

## Detailed Design
[Architecture diagrams, migration sequence, fallback plan]

### Phase 1 (Q1): Enable New Architecture for dev
- Enable newArchEnabled=true in gradle.properties
- Identify incompatible 3rd-party modules (30 modules, 8 incompatible)
- Create compatibility layer for unmigrated modules

### Phase 2 (Q2): Migrate critical native modules
- Camera, Payments, Analytics → TurboModules
- Migrate ViewManagers to Fabric components

### Phase 3 (Q3): Roll out to production (10% → 50% → 100%)

## Tradeoffs
| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|----------|------|------|
| Full migration | Maximum perf gains | High risk, 6mo effort |
| Incremental | Lower risk | Longer timeline, complexity |
| Stay on old arch | Zero effort | Miss perf gains, tech debt |

## Risks & Mitigations
- 8 incompatible modules → fork + migrate (3 engineers, 4 weeks)
- Regression risk → feature flags per platform + A/B test

## Success Metrics
- TTI < 2.0s on P50 Android
- JS → Native call latency < 5ms (was 15ms)
- Crash rate maintained < 0.1%

## Alternatives Considered
[...]

## Open Questions
1. Should we migrate iOS and Android simultaneously or sequentially?</code></pre>

  <h2>Technical Debt Prioritization Framework</h2>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
TECH DEBT DECISION MATRIX

                HIGH BUSINESS IMPACT
                         │
    ┌────────────────────┼────────────────────┐
    │                    │                    │
    │   Migrate now      │  Strategic project  │
    │   (quick wins)     │  (plan Q-roadmap)   │
    │                    │                    │
LOW ──────────────────────────────────────── HIGH
EFFORT                   │                   EFFORT
    │                    │                    │
    │   Tolerate          │  Don't do it        │
    │   (document it)     │  (ROI negative)     │
    │                    │                    │
    └────────────────────┼────────────────────┘
                         │
                LOW BUSINESS IMPACT

EXAMPLES:
- Bridge → New Arch: HIGH impact, HIGH effort → Strategic Q-project
- Fix deprecated API warning: LOW impact, LOW effort → Sprint cleanup
- Rewrite working state management: LOW impact, HIGH effort → Reject
- Fix known startup ANR: HIGH impact, LOW effort → Do now
</pre>
  </div>

  <h2>Code Review Philosophy</h2>

  <pre data-lang="Markdown"><code>## Staff Engineer Code Review Principles

### As Reviewer:
- Distinguish blocking vs non-blocking feedback
  - [BLOCKING]: Bug, security issue, architecture violation → must fix
  - [SUGGESTION]: Improvement I'd make, author decides
  - [NIT]: Minor style preference → shouldn't block merge
  - [QUESTION]: I don't understand this, explain or simplify

- Review for:
  1. Correctness (bugs, edge cases, race conditions)
  2. Security (auth, input validation, data exposure)
  3. Performance (renders, memory, network)
  4. Maintainability (will future-you understand this?)
  5. Tests (coverage, quality, not just quantity)

- Acknowledge good work ("Nice use of useSyncExternalStore here!")

### As Author:
- PR description: WHY, not just WHAT. Include screenshots/video
- Keep PRs small (<400 lines). Large PRs get rubber-stamped.
- Self-review before requesting review
- Respond to all comments (even if "acknowledged" or "won't fix: [reason]")
</code></pre>

