      <strong>Approach: curiosity before judgment.</strong>
      <br><br>
      "First, I have a private 1:1 — not to confront but to understand. 'I've noticed X, help me understand your perspective.' Often there's a legitimate reason: the process is genuinely too slow, tests are testing the wrong things, documentation is never read. I take that seriously.
      <br><br>
      If the process is bad, fix the process first. If it's a speed issue, we negotiate: a 24h SLA on PR reviews, lightweight doc templates.
      <br><br>
      If after addressing concerns, the behavior continues: make the expectation explicit with clear language — 'This is a team requirement, not optional.' Connect it to team health, not rules: 'When PRs go unreviewed, junior engineers can't grow. That costs the team.'
      <br><br>
      If it still continues, escalate to management with specifics and context — not to punish, but because at this point it's a management conversation about role expectations. I never let one person's resistance excuse others from the process or normalize the exception."
