<section class="section" id="system-design">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-num">11</div>
    <div class="section-title-wrap">
      <div class="section-tag">Architecture at Scale</div>
      <h1 class="section-title">Advanced Mobile System Design</h1>
      <p class="section-desc">Offline sync, CRDTs, real-time chat, healthcare SaaS, multi-tenant architecture, and complete whiteboard interview walkthroughs.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>System Design: Build a Chat App Like WhatsApp</h2>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
CHAT SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE

Mobile Client                  Backend Infrastructure
─────────────                  ──────────────────────

  React Native App
  ├── Local SQLite DB         ◄── Offline-first
  ├── Message queue           ◄── Pending sends
  └── WebSocket client

  Connection Layer:
  ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ WebSocket Gateway (uWS / Socket.io)                │
  │ - Stateful: userId → connectionId mapping          │
  │ - Redis Pub/Sub: fan-out to all user connections   │
  │ - Horizontal scale: 100k concurrent users/node     │
  └─────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────┘
                    │
  ┌─────────────────▼──────────────────────────────────┐
  │ Message Service                                     │
  │ - Persist to Cassandra (time-series, append-only)  │
  │ - Publish to Kafka topic: messages.{conversationId}│
  │ - Fan-out service: push to offline users via FCM   │
  └─────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────┘
                    │
  ┌─────────────────▼──────────────────────────────────┐
  │ Cassandra Schema                                    │
  │ partition_key: conversation_id                      │
  │ clustering: timestamp DESC (latest first)           │
  │ Max query: SELECT * WHERE convo_id=X LIMIT 50      │
  └────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

DELIVERY GUARANTEES:
  - At-least-once: client retries until ACK received
  - Deduplication: server-side idempotency key (client_msg_id)
  - Ordering: Lamport timestamps + server-assigned sequence

MESSAGE STATUS:
  Sending → Sent (server ACK) → Delivered (recipient online) → Read
  Each state change: server event → WebSocket push → client update
</pre>
  </div>

  <h2>Offline Sync & Conflict Resolution</h2>

  <h3>CRDTs — Conflict-free Replicated Data Types</h3>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
CRDT USE CASES IN MOBILE

Problem: User edits same document on two devices while offline.
Both sync when online. Whose edit wins?

CRDT TYPES:
─────────────

G-Counter (grow-only):
  Device A: {deviceA: 5, deviceB: 0}
  Device B: {deviceA: 0, deviceB: 3}
  Merge:    {deviceA: 5, deviceB: 3} → value = 8
  Use case: unread count, analytics

LWW Register (Last-Write-Wins):
  Use physical or Hybrid Logical Clocks (HLC)
  HLC: (physical_time, logical_counter, node_id)
  Causally consistent ordering across devices

OR-Set (Observed-Remove Set):
  Add(item) gets unique tag. Remove removes ALL tags.
  No issue with concurrent add/remove
  Use case: shared shopping lists, tags

RGA (Replicated Growable Array):
  For collaborative text editing
  Each character gets unique ID
  Concurrent inserts: deterministic ordering by ID
  Used by: Notion, Figma's real-time collaboration

MOBILE IMPLEMENTATION:
  - Yjs (JS CRDT library, works in RN)
  - Automerge
  - Store CRDT state in SQLite
  - Sync deltas (not full state) over WebSocket
</pre>
  </div>

  <pre data-lang="TypeScript"><code>// Yjs offline sync in React Native
import * as Y from 'yjs';
import { WebsocketProvider } from 'y-websocket';
import { IndexeddbPersistence } from 'y-indexeddb'; // or SQLite adapter

const ydoc = new Y.Doc();

// Persist locally (survives app kills)
const persistence = new IndexeddbPersistence('document-123', ydoc);

// Sync with server when online
const provider = new WebsocketProvider('ws://api.myapp.com/sync', 'document-123', ydoc, {
  connect: false, // don't connect yet
});

// Connect only when online
NetInfo.addEventListener(state => {
  if (state.isConnected && !provider.wsconnected) {
    provider.connect();
  } else if (!state.isConnected) {
    provider.disconnect(); // graceful, saves battery
  }
});

// Collaborative text
const text = ydoc.getText('content');
text.insert(0, 'Hello World'); // conflict-free, auto-merged</code></pre>

  <h2>Healthcare / Hospital SaaS Architecture</h2>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
HOSPITAL ERP MOBILE ARCHITECTURE

Security Requirements: HIPAA / HL7 FHIR compliant

┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    Security Layer                         │
│  - Certificate pinning (prevent MITM)                     │
│  - Biometric auth + session token (15min expiry)          │
│  - Jailbreak/Root detection (SafetyNet, DeviceCheck)      │
│  - Data at rest: Keychain/EncryptedSharedPrefs ONLY       │
│  - Screenshot prevention (FLAG_SECURE on Android)         │
│  - Screen recording blocked (iOS UIScreen.isCaptured)     │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

Multi-Tenant Data Isolation:
  - Row-level security in PostgreSQL (hospital_id in every table)
  - Separate Kafka topics per hospital
  - Separate S3 buckets per hospital (DICOM images)
  - API gateway: JWT contains hospital_id claim
  - Mobile: tenant config from secure remote config

Offline-First for Clinical Use:
  - Doctors need patient data even in dead zones (basement wards)
  - SQLite WAL mode for concurrent reads
  - Sync critical: patient allergies, medications always cached
  - Sync non-critical: historical lab results on-demand
  - Conflict resolution: server-wins for clinical data (safety)
  - Audit trail: every local edit timestamped, synced for compliance

Real-time Features:
  - Nurse call system: WebSocket push (life-critical: P0)
  - Lab results: push notification when ready
  - Bed management: real-time occupancy updates (Kafka → SSE)
  - Medication reminders: local notifications + server confirmation
</pre>
  </div>

  <h2>System Design: Video Streaming App</h2>

  <div class="diagram">
<pre>
VIDEO STREAMING ARCHITECTURE (Netflix-style)

Upload Pipeline:
  Camera → RN → multipart upload → S3 (raw)
                                       │
                                  Transcoding Service
                                  (FFmpeg in Lambda)
                                       │
                        ┌─────────────┼─────────────┐
                        ▼             ▼             ▼
                   360p/H264     720p/H264     1080p/HEVC
                        └─────────────┼─────────────┘
                                      │
                              HLS segments (.m3u8)
                              stored in S3
                                      │
                                  CloudFront CDN

Playback in RN:
  react-native-video (ExoPlayer / AVPlayer)
  ├── Adaptive bitrate (ABR): switches quality based on bandwidth
  ├── Buffer ahead: 30s minimum
  ├── DRM: Widevine (Android) + FairPlay (iOS)
  ├── Offline: download encrypted segments to device
  └── Picture-in-Picture: platform native API

Performance:
  - Pre-buffer on WiFi while on feed
  - Low-res thumbnail preview on scrub
  - Thumbnail sprite sheets for timeline previews
  - TTFV (Time To First Video): < 1.5s target
  - P50 stall rate: < 0.5% per 60s
</pre>
  </div>

  <div class="iq-box">
    <div class="iq-header">
      <span class="iq-label">System Design Interview</span>
      <span class="iq-level lvl-faang">FAANG Level</span>
    </div>
    <div class="iq-q">Design a ride-sharing app's driver location tracking system. 5 million active drivers, 1 billion location updates/hour.</div>
    <div class="iq-a">
      <strong>Mobile client:</strong> Driver app sends location every 4s on active ride, 15s when waiting. Uses fused location (best accuracy/battery balance). Batches updates: 3 locations per HTTP POST → 3x fewer connections. Uses WebSocket only for incoming ride requests (server→client), not location upload.
      <br><br>
      <strong>Ingestion:</strong> Location updates → API Gateway → Kafka (topic: location.updates, partitioned by driver_id). 1B/hr = 277k/s. Kafka handles this with 20 brokers, replication factor 3.
      <br><br>
      <strong>Processing:</strong> Stream processor (Flink/Spark Streaming) consumes Kafka, writes to Redis Geo (sorted set with geohash). Redis can do 100k geo writes/sec per node. 277k/s needs 3 Redis nodes.
      <br><br>
      <strong>Query (rider app):</strong> "Find drivers within 2km" → Redis GEORADIUS → returns driver IDs → lookup driver details from DB → send to rider app.
      <br><br>
      <strong>Rider app receives:</strong> Websocket push when driver moves. Only sends delta if driver moved >50m → reduces update frequency 80%.
      <br><br>
      <strong>Map rendering:</strong> Drivers are Animated markers on Mapbox. Interpolate between updates (smooth movement). Only re-render changed drivers (memo keyed by driverId).
    </div>
  </div>

</section>

