<section class="section" id="interview">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-num">13</div>
    <div class="section-title-wrap">
      <div class="section-tag">Interview Preparation</div>
      <h1 class="section-title">Complete Interview Question Bank</h1>
      <p class="section-desc">200+ questions with answers across all domains — Senior, Staff, and FAANG levels. Red flags, follow-ups, and what interviewers actually evaluate.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>React Native Core</h2>

  <div class="iq-box">
    <div class="iq-header"><span class="iq-label">RN Core</span><span class="iq-level lvl-senior">Senior</span></div>
    <div class="iq-q">What is the difference between the Old Architecture and New Architecture in React Native?</div>
    <div class="iq-a">
      <strong>Old Architecture:</strong> JS ↔ Native communication via async JSON bridge. Layout in JS (YogaJS). Two trees: JS shadow tree + native view tree synchronized asynchronously. Native modules loaded eagerly. All data serialized/deserialized.
      <br><br>
      <strong>New Architecture (JSI + Fabric + TurboModules):</strong>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>JSI:</strong> JS directly references C++ objects — no serialization, synchronous calls possible</li>
        <li><strong>TurboModules:</strong> Native modules loaded on-demand via code generation, strongly typed via TypeScript specs</li>
        <li><strong>Fabric:</strong> C++ renderer, synchronous layout, Concurrent Mode support, direct UIKit/View mount</li>
        <li><strong>Codegen:</strong> TypeScript → C++ bindings automatically, type-safe at compile time</li>
      </ul>
      <strong>Impact:</strong> 40-60% startup improvement, sub-5ms native call latency, React 18 Concurrent Mode works correctly.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="iq-box">
    <div class="iq-header"><span class="iq-label">RN Core</span><span class="iq-level lvl-senior">Senior</span></div>
    <div class="iq-q">How does Metro bundler work? What is its role in the development vs production build?</div>
    <div class="iq-a">
      Metro is RN's JavaScript bundler. It: (1) resolves module imports using its resolver (supports platform-specific files: <code>.ios.js</code>, <code>.android.js</code>), (2) transforms files via Babel (TS→JS, JSX→React.createElement), (3) bundles into a single JS bundle with module map, (4) serves via dev server with HMR in development.
      <br><br>
      <strong>Dev:</strong> Serves bundle from Metro dev server. Fast refresh via WebSocket connection. Source maps inline.
      <br><br>
      <strong>Production:</strong> Generates <code>index.android.bundle</code> / <code>main.jsbundle</code>. Runs Hermes compiler on the bundle → <code>.hbc</code> bytecode. Source maps generated separately for crash symbolication. Bundle split into RAM bundle format for lazy loading (optional).
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="iq-box">
    <div class="iq-header"><span class="iq-label">RN Architecture</span><span class="iq-level lvl-staff">Staff</span></div>
    <div class="iq-q">How would you design a TurboModule for high-frequency sensor data (1000 readings/second from an accelerometer)?</div>
    <div class="iq-a">
      <strong>Key challenge:</strong> 1000 events/sec via JSI events would flood the JS thread.
      <br><br>
      <strong>Design:</strong>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Native-side batching:</strong> Collect readings in a ring buffer on a dedicated native thread. Every 16ms (one frame), flush up to 16 readings as a single batch event to JS.</li>
        <li><strong>JSI NativeEventEmitter replacement:</strong> Use a direct JSI callback registered once — <code>setDataCallback(callback)</code>. Each frame calls the callback with a typed array (Float32Array) directly mapped to C++ memory — zero copy.</li>
        <li><strong>Back-pressure:</strong> If JS can't keep up (callback not returned before next flush), drop oldest readings, emit a "dropped" count.</li>
        <li><strong>Worklet offloading:</strong> If processing is numeric (FFT, peak detection), run in a Reanimated worklet on the UI thread, bypassing JS entirely.</li>
        <li><strong>API design:</strong> <code>startStream(intervalMs, onData, onError)</code> returns a subscription handle. <code>stopStream(handle)</code> cancels the native source.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="iq-box">
    <div class="iq-header"><span class="iq-label">Performance</span><span class="iq-level lvl-senior">Senior</span></div>
    <div class="iq-q">A FlatList with 500 items is janky on mid-range Android. Walk through your optimization process.</div>
    <div class="iq-a">
      <strong>Step 1: Profile first.</strong> Flipper → Performance → enable "JS FPS" and "UI FPS". Identify: is it the JS thread or UI thread that's dropping frames?
      <br><br>
      <strong>JS thread drops:</strong>
      <ul>
        <li>Check renderItem for expensive computation → memoize</li>
        <li>Check if parent re-renders too often → memo + context split</li>
        <li>Remove excessive console.log in list items</li>
      </ul>
      <strong>UI thread drops (GPU overdraw):</strong>
      <ul>
        <li>Enable "Show overdraw" in Developer Options → red areas = overdraw</li>
        <li>Remove unnecessary backgroundColor on nested views</li>
        <li>Replace View elevation+shadow with pre-rasterized shadows</li>
      </ul>
      <strong>List-specific:</strong>
      <ul>
        <li>Migrate to FlashList with <code>estimatedItemSize</code></li>
        <li>Add <code>getItemType</code> for mixed content</li>
        <li>Use <code>removeClippedSubviews={true}</code></li>
        <li>Reduce <code>maxToRenderPerBatch</code> to 5, increase <code>windowSize</code> to 5</li>
        <li>Move images to <code>Image</code> with explicit width/height (no layout recalculation)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Android & iOS Deep Dive Questions</h2>

  <div class="iq-box">
    <div class="iq-header"><span class="iq-label">Android</span><span class="iq-level lvl-senior">Senior</span></div>
    <div class="iq-q">What is the difference between compileSdkVersion, targetSdkVersion, and minSdkVersion in Android?</div>
    <div class="iq-a">
      <strong>minSdkVersion:</strong> Minimum Android version your app supports. Devices below this won't install the app. Set to 24 (Android 7.0) for modern RN apps.
      <br><br>
      <strong>compileSdkVersion:</strong> SDK version used to compile your code. Use the latest (34). Gives access to latest APIs and compiler checks. Doesn't affect runtime.
      <br><br>
      <strong>targetSdkVersion:</strong> The version your app is optimized for. Android changes behavior based on this: if target=33+, you must request BLUETOOTH_SCAN permission (not just BLUETOOTH). If target=34+, foreground service must declare type. Raising targetSdk can break your app — requires testing all behavior changes.
      <br><br>
      <strong>Google Play requirement:</strong> New apps must target API 34+ (2024). Updates must target within 1 year of latest release.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="iq-box">
    <div class="iq-header"><span class="iq-label">iOS</span><span class="iq-level lvl-staff">Staff</span></div>
    <div class="iq-q">Explain how to implement background location tracking on iOS in a React Native app without getting your app rejected by Apple.</div>
    <div class="iq-a">
      <strong>Entitlements required:</strong> <code>location-always-and-when-in-use</code> background mode in Info.plist. Add <code>UIBackgroundModes: [location]</code>.
      <br><br>
      <strong>Permission flow:</strong> Request "When In Use" first → if granted, then request "Always" with explanation dialog. Never request "Always" first (App Store rejection).
      <br><br>
      <strong>Implementation:</strong> Use <code>CLLocationManager</code> with <code>startMonitoringSignificantLocationChanges()</code> (battery-efficient) for background, not <code>startUpdatingLocation</code> (foreground-only unless you have the background entitlement).
      <br><br>
      <strong>Apple's rules:</strong> Location must be core to your app's functionality. Your App Store description must explain why. If you request "Always" for analytics or ads → rejection. Write a compelling NSLocationAlwaysAndWhenInUseUsageDescription.
      <br><br>
      <strong>Battery:</strong> Use <code>distanceFilter = 50</code> (meters), <code>desiredAccuracy = kCLLocationAccuracyHundredMeters</code>. Only use high accuracy when actively navigating.
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Behavioral & Leadership Questions</h2>

  <div class="iq-box">
    <div class="iq-header"><span class="iq-label">Leadership</span><span class="iq-level lvl-staff">Staff</span></div>
    <div class="iq-q">Tell me about a technical migration you led. What was your approach and what would you do differently?</div>
    <div class="iq-a">
      <strong>Structure: Context → Approach → Results → Retrospective</strong>
      <br><br>
      <strong>Strong answer template:</strong> "We had a 3-year-old React Native app on the Old Architecture. Startup time was 4.5s on P50 Android — a top-5 user complaint. I proposed migrating to New Architecture.
      <br><br>
      My approach: I wrote an RFC, got buy-in from 3 teams, created a migration runbook. Used feature flags to enable New Arch per platform independently. Prioritized: found 8 incompatible libraries, triaged into 'migrate', 'fork+patch', 'replace'. Ran Old Arch and New Arch in parallel builds for 6 weeks for A/B comparison.
      <br><br>
      Results: TTI improved from 4.5s to 2.1s on P50. Zero regression in crash rate during rollout. Unlocked React 18 concurrent features.
      <br><br>
      What I'd do differently: I underestimated the library compatibility work by 2x. Next time I'd do a full library audit and build a compatibility matrix before committing to the timeline."
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Coding Round — Common Patterns</h2>

  <pre data-lang="TypeScript"><code>// Classic FAANG RN coding question: Debounced search with cancellation

function useDebounceSearch(query: string, delay = 300) {
  const [results, setResults] = useState<SearchResult[]>([]);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
  const [error, setError] = useState<Error | null>(null);
  const abortRef = useRef<AbortController | null>(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    if (!query.trim()) {
      setResults([]);
      return;
    }

    // Debounce: don't fire on every keystroke
    const timeoutId = setTimeout(async () => {
      // Cancel previous in-flight request
      abortRef.current?.abort();
      abortRef.current = new AbortController();

      setLoading(true);
      setError(null);

      try {
        const data = await searchAPI(query, {
          signal: abortRef.current.signal
        });
        setResults(data);
      } catch (e) {
        if ((e as Error).name !== 'AbortError') {
          setError(e as Error);
        }
        // AbortError is expected on fast typing — ignore
      } finally {
        setLoading(false);
      }
    }, delay);

    return () => {
      clearTimeout(timeoutId);
      abortRef.current?.abort(); // cancel on unmount
    };
  }, [query, delay]);

  return { results, loading, error };
}</code></pre>

  <pre data-lang="TypeScript"><code">// Implement a useInterval hook that pauses on background
function useInterval(callback: () => void, delay: number | null) {
  const savedCallback = useRef(callback);

  // Keep ref up to date (avoids stale closure)
  useEffect(() => {
    savedCallback.current = callback;
  }, [callback]);

  useEffect(() => {
    if (delay === null) return; // null = paused

    const id = setInterval(() => savedCallback.current(), delay);
    return () => clearInterval(id);
  }, [delay]);
}

// Usage with AppState (pause when backgrounded)
function LivePrice({ symbol }: { symbol: string }) {
  const appState = useRef(AppState.currentState);
  const [active, setActive] = useState(true);

  useEffect(() => {
    const sub = AppState.addEventListener('change', state => {
      setActive(state === 'active');
      appState.current = state;
    });
    return () => sub.remove();
  }, []);

  useInterval(
    () => fetchPrice(symbol),
    active ? 3000 : null // pause when backgrounded
  );
}</code></pre>

</section>

<!-- ===== SECTION 14: ROADMAP ===== -->
<section class="section" id="roadmap">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-num">14</div>
    <div class="section-title-wrap">
      <div class="section-tag">Career Development</div>
      <h1 class="section-title">Staff-Level Roadmap</h1>
      <p class="section-desc">6-month and 12-month plans with weekly milestones, mock interview cadence, GitHub projects, and FAANG-specific preparation tracks.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>6-Month Roadmap to Staff Engineer</h2>

  <div class="timeline">
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-title">Month 1 — Foundation Audit</div>
      <div class="tl-body">
        <strong>Week 1–2:</strong> Assess gaps. Work through this manual. Mark sections you can't explain from first principles.<br>
        <strong>Week 3–4:</strong> Deep dive: React internals + JS engine. Read React source (packages/react-reconciler). Explain Fiber tree traversal aloud.
        <br><strong>Project:</strong> Build a mini reconciler from scratch (100 lines) to internalize Fiber concepts.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-title">Month 2 — Native Engineering</div>
      <div class="tl-body">
        <strong>Week 1–2:</strong> Android deep dive. Build a TurboModule from scratch (camera, BLE, or custom sensor). Write JUnit tests.<br>
        <strong>Week 3–4:</strong> iOS deep dive. Port the same module to Swift + Objective-C++. Profile with Instruments.
        <br><strong>Project:</strong> Open-source a production-grade TurboModule with full tests + README.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-title">Month 3 — Architecture & Systems</div>
      <div class="tl-body">
        <strong>Week 1–2:</strong> System design practice. Do 3 system design problems (chat, video, maps). Record yourself explaining.
        <br><strong>Week 3–4:</strong> Architecture patterns. Refactor an existing project to Clean Architecture. Write the RFC.
        <br><strong>Project:</strong> Build a full offline-first app with Yjs sync and conflict visualization.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-title">Month 4 — Performance Engineering</div>
      <div class="tl-body">
        <strong>Week 1–2:</strong> Performance profiling. Take an existing app and systematically optimize startup time by 30%. Document every step.
        <br><strong>Week 3–4:</strong> Reanimated deep dive. Build 5 complex gesture-driven animations. Benchmark JS Animated vs Reanimated.
        <br><strong>Project:</strong> Open source a performance case study blog post with Perfetto/Instruments screenshots.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-title">Month 5 — Interview Practice</div>
      <div class="tl-body">
        <strong>Week 1–2:</strong> Coding rounds. 2 LeetCode mediums/day (focus: arrays, trees, graphs, sliding window). Practice in TypeScript.
        <br><strong>Week 3–4:</strong> Mock interviews. 2 mock system design, 2 mock behavioral, 2 mock technical per week. Use Pramp, Interviewing.io, or peer mocks.
        <br><strong>Goal:</strong> 20 total mock sessions this month.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-title">Month 6 — FAANG Applications</div>
      <div class="tl-body">
        <strong>Week 1:</strong> Polish GitHub (pin your TurboModule + performance case study). Update LinkedIn. Write STAR stories for 10 behavioral questions.
        <br><strong>Week 2–3:</strong> Apply to 5–10 companies. Start with less-preferred to warm up. Schedule FAANG rounds for Week 4+.
        <br><strong>Week 4:</strong> Final prep — review every weak area flagged in mocks. Rest + confidence.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>12-Month Staff/Architect Roadmap</h2>

  <div class="roadmap-track">
    <div class="roadmap-week">
      <div class="roadmap-week-label">Q1 — Depth</div>
      <h4>Technical Foundation</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Complete all 14 sections of this manual</li>
        <li>Build 3 production-quality open-source projects</li>
        <li>Contribute to React Native core (even docs)</li>
        <li>Read: "Designing Data-Intensive Applications"</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="roadmap-week">
      <div class="roadmap-week-label">Q2 — Breadth</div>
      <h4>Systems Thinking</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Build a full-stack feature end-to-end</li>
        <li>Set up a complete CI/CD pipeline</li>
        <li>Design + implement an offline-first app</li>
        <li>Write 3 technical blog posts</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="roadmap-week">
      <div class="roadmap-week-label">Q3 — Leadership</div>
      <h4>Influence & Communication</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Lead a migration or major refactor at work</li>
        <li>Write an RFC and get consensus</li>
        <li>Mentor a junior to mid-level engineer</li>
        <li>Present at a meetup or conference</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="roadmap-week">
      <div class="roadmap-week-label">Q4 — Execution</div>
      <h4>Interviews + Career Move</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>30 total mock interviews across all formats</li>
        <li>Apply to target companies</li>
        <li>Negotiate offers with competing leverage</li>
        <li>Plan 90-day onboarding for new role</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Weekly Study Plan Template</h2>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Day</th><th>Focus</th><th>Activity</th><th>Time</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Monday</td><td>Coding</td><td>2 LeetCode problems (timed, 45min each)</td><td>1.5h</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Tuesday</td><td>Deep Dive</td><td>Study one section of this manual in depth</td><td>1.5h</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Wednesday</td><td>Build</td><td>Work on open-source project / TurboModule</td><td>2h</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Thursday</td><td>System Design</td><td>Design one system, draw diagram, explain aloud</td><td>1.5h</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Friday</td><td>Behavioral</td><td>Write/refine 2 STAR stories, mock with peer</td><td>1h</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Saturday</td><td>Mock Interview</td><td>Full mock (45min technical + 20min behavioral)</td><td>1.5h</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Sunday</td><td>Review</td><td>Review week's notes, update knowledge gaps list</td><td>1h</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2>GitHub Project Ideas for Portfolio</h2>

  <div class="card-grid">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">🔧 Production TurboModule Starter</div>
      <div class="card-body">Complete TurboModule with: Android (Kotlin + JNI), iOS (Swift + ObjC++), TypeScript spec, codegen, Jest mocks, unit tests, CI. 500+ GitHub stars is realistic for quality work.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">📊 RN Performance Dashboard</div>
      <div class="card-body">App that benchmarks itself: startup time, render count, memory, FPS — all displayed live. Shows before/after of optimization techniques. Educational + demonstrates expertise.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">🔄 Offline-First Todo + Sync</div>
      <div class="card-body">Full CRDT-based collaborative todo app. Yjs + SQLite + WebSocket sync. Conflict visualization. Clear demo of offline → online reconciliation. Deploy backend to Fly.io.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">🎨 Reanimated UI Library</div>
      <div class="card-body">5–10 complex gesture-driven animations: bottom sheet, swipeable rows, drag-to-reorder, pinch-to-zoom map. Benchmarked at 60fps on mid-range Android. Full documentation.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>The Staff Engineer Mindset</h2>

  <div class="callout callout-success">
    <span class="callout-icon">🎯</span>
    <div class="callout-content">
      <div class="callout-title">What Separates Good from Great at the Staff Level</div>
      <strong>Technical Excellence is table stakes.</strong> Every Staff candidate can code. What interviewers at FAANG evaluate beyond coding:
      <br><br>
      <strong>1. Judgment under ambiguity.</strong> Given incomplete information, can you drive to a decision? Propose options, state tradeoffs, recommend one.
      <br><br>
      <strong>2. Scope amplification.</strong> A Senior engineer solves their task. A Staff engineer asks: "How do I solve this in a way that makes all future similar tasks easier for the entire org?"
      <br><br>
      <strong>3. Written communication.</strong> RFCs, postmortems, design docs. Can you influence without being in the room? Your writing is your leverage at scale.
      <br><br>
      <strong>4. Constructive tension.</strong> Push back on bad ideas from anyone — PM, engineering manager, senior leadership — with data, not ego. Then execute the final decision fully, even if it's not yours.
      <br><br>
      <strong>5. Make others better.</strong> Code review, mentoring, architecture guidance. Your impact is multiplied through the people around you.
    </div>
  </div>

</section>

